# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 10th-mountain-division
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The **87th Mountain Infantry Regiment** is an infantry regiment in the United States Army.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The regiment's 1st and 2nd Battalions are light infantry units assigned to the 1st and 2nd Brigade Combat Teams respectively of the 10th Mountain Division located at Fort Drum, New York.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The 3rd Battalion was active in the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The 4th Battalion was a Regular Army unit assigned to the 3rd Brigade Combat Team of the 25th Infantry Division (Light) at Schofield Barracks, Hawaii.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The 87th Mountain Infantry Battalion was activated on 15 November 1941 at Fort Lewis, Washington, with Lieutenant Colonel Onslow S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] This unit was the first American unit of mountain troops.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] According to Captain George Earle, 12 officers and one enlisted man had met at Fort Lewis and were designated as the cadre of this battalion.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] However, another source reports that when its first recruit, Charles McLane, reported for duty at Fort Lewis 8 December of that year, and asked to be directed to his battalion.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Over the following months, skilled skiers recruited by the National Ski Patrol, mostly Europeans, some of whom had fled the encroachment of Nazi Germany, arrived at Fort Lewis.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Peer Shelton notes that "as the companies of the first battalion filled up—A Company, then B Company, and so on—the roster ... became a kind of who's who of American skiing." Best known of them was Norwegian Torger Tokle.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Lieutenant Colonel Rolfe negotiated a deal with the National Park Service to lease Paradise Inn through May for Army use, and the growing battalion trained there.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] In the spring of 1942, the unit was reorganized as the 87th Mountain Infantry Regiment and a second and third battalions added.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] In the summer of 1942 the regiment moved to Camp Hale, Colorado.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] On 11 June 1943, the regiment departed for Fort Ord where they had training in amphibious landing, then on 27 July the regiment was detached from the 10th Mountain Division and sailed to the Aleutian Islands as part of Amphibious Task Force 9.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Also included in Task Force 9 were the First Special Service Force and the 13th Canadian Infantry Brigade.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] At the conclusion of the campaign, the 87th returned to the United States via Canada and went to Camp Carson, Colorado, arriving by 1 January 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] It was reunited with the 10th Mountain Division in the middle of February 1944, replacing the 90th Infantry Regiment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] As part of the 10th Mountain Division, the regiment sailed from Newport News 3 January 1945 on the SS *West Point* for Italy, landing in Naples 13 January.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] There it took part in the Italian Campaign, seeing action in Operation Encore (19 February—5 March).
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The regiment took part in the Spring 1945 offensive in Italy, driving north from the Apennine Mountains on 20 April into the Po valley west of Bologna.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Using plywood assault boats scrounged by the Divisional engineering unit, on 23 April Company A of the 87th Mountain Infantry was the first Allied unit to cross the Po river.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The regiment continued to slice through the disintegrating enemy units, reaching Lake Garda days before the capitulation of the German forces in Italy on 2 May.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] While part of the occupying force, the regiment was redeployed east to the vicinity of Udine on 19 May as a show of force to the Yugoslavians, intended to discourage them from occupying territory they disputed with Italy.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Until the regiment left for Caporetto, Italy on 17 July, its men served as peace keepers between Yugoslavian soldiers and Italian partisans, manning positions along the Isonzo River from Plezzo to Tolmino.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] From Caporetto, the regiment proceeded to Naples where they left Italy on the SS *Mt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The Regiment later claimed to have been the first infantry regiment to have fought in both the Pacific and European Theaters.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The 87th Infantry was again assigned to the 10th Mountain Division on 18 June 1948, where it was reactivated as a training division at Fort Riley, Kansas.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] In January 1954, 10th Division became a standard infantry division and was sent to West Germany.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] It was inactivated on 14 June 1958 at Fort Benning, GA.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] During this era the Army reorganized its combat forces, abandoning three tactical infantry regiments per division for five battle groups of five companies each, known as the Pentomic organization.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Effective 1 July 1957 the lineage of Company A, 87th Infantry Regiment was reorganized and redesignated as HHC, 1st Battle Group, 87th Infantry and remained assigned to the 10th Infantry Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] It was relieved effective 14 June 1958 from the 10th and reassigned to the 2d Infantry Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The unit was reorganized and redesignated on 15 February 1963 as the 1st Battalion, 87th Infantry and relieved on 4 September 1963 from assignment to the 2d Infantry Division and assigned to the 8th Infantry Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] It remained there until it the lineage was inactivated 1 October 1983 in Germany and relieved from assignment to the 8th Infantry Division when the unit was reflagged with a different regimental designation.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] On 2 May 1987 the battalion was assigned to the 10th Mountain Division and activated at Fort Drum, New York.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The lineage of Company B was inactivated effective 1 July 1957 in Germany, redesignated as HHC, 2d Battle Group, 87th Infantry and relieved from assignment to the 10th Infantry Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] It was redesignated on 25 January 1963 as Headquarters and Headquarters Company, 2d Battalion, 87th Infantry, and assigned to the 2d Infantry Division (organic elements concurrently constituted) and activated on 15 February 1963 at Fort Benning, Georgia.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] That same year it was relieve from assignment to the 2d Infantry Division and assigned to the 8th Infantry Division, then in Germany, where it was inactivated on 1 May 1966.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] It was reactivated on 31 August 1973 when the division's 1st Brigade (Airborne) in Mainz-Gonsenheim was taken off jump status and the 2d Battalion (Airborne), 509th Infantry was reorganized and reflagged as the 2d Battalion, (Mechanized) 87th Infantry.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] On 16 June 1986 the battalion colors were again inactivated when the unit was reflagged as a battalion of the 8th Infantry, pairing it with CONUS-based elements of the 8th Infantry under the 4th Infantry Division at Fort Carson, Colorado.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] On 2 May 1988 the battalion was assigned to the 10th Mountain Division and activated at Fort Drum, New York.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Two companies of 87th Infantry were in Vietnam during the war, both as Rifle Security units.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The first was Company C, 87th Infantry, which was attached to the 92d Military Police Battalion guarding Tan Son Nhut Air Base.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] It was later assigned to Long Binh Post under the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Coming from Fort Lewis, WA, it was in Vietnam from 29 November 1966 to 26 November 1972.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Also coming from Fort Lewis was Company D, 87th Infantry, which was attached to the 95th Military Police Battalion at Long Binh from 1 December 1966 to 6 November 1969.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The unit served a second tour in Vietnam from 30 June 1971 to 30 April 1972 when it guarded installations of the 26th General Support Group at Tấn Mỹ.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Both companies had an authorized strength of 151 in 1968 and 160 in 1971.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Effective 1 January 1975 the lineage of Company C, 87th Infantry was withdrawn from the Regular Army, allotted to the Army Reserve, redesignated as HHC, 3d Battalion, 87th Infantry and activated at Fort Carson, CO.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The battalion was authorized 38 officers, 4 warrant officers and 692 enlisted personnel (later changed to 37, 2, and 754, respectively) with headquarters in Building 2344 at Fort Carson as a unit of the 96th Army Reserve Command.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] In addition to the 96th shoulder sleeve insignia, members of the unit wore color 10th Division shoulder sleeve insignia on the left front pocket of fatigue shirts to signify the battalion's historical link to the then-inactive division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Mountain tabs were not worn over the patch as they were almost impossible to find before the division was reactivated at Fort Drum and tabs went into production again.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] A detachment of the battalion's Company C was located at 158 Bodo Drive, Durango, CO 81301; it was inactivated on 16 October 1984.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Company C moved from the Denver Federal Center to 10455 East 25th Avenue, Aurora, CO 80011 effective 1 June 1985, and then to 1788 Helena Street, also in Aurora, effective 1 February 1990.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The battalion was ordered into active military service on 17 January 1991.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] It arrived at Fort Carson for training on 19 January 1991 and moved to Germany on 5 February 1991.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] There it performed anti-terrorist security missions for V Corps.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] It returned to Fort Carson on 1 May 1991, and personnel were released for terminal leave on 15 May 1991 as the battalion reverted to reserve status.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] By early 1991 HHC had relocated to Building 8932, Duncan-Selix USAR Center, Fort Carson, CO.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Effective 16 September 1991 the Combat Support Company (formerly Support Company) was inactivated.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The battalion was organized effective 16 September 1992 to consist of 34 officers, 2 warrant officers, and 547 enlisted personnel as a light infantry unit.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] During the post-Cold War drawdown, when most reserve component combat arms units were concentrated in the Army National Guard, the battalion was inactivated on 15 September 1994 at Fort Carson.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Effective 16 June 1986 the lineage of World War II's Company D was redesignated as HHC, 4th Battalion, 87th Infantry Regiment and assigned to the 25th Infantry Division at Schofield Barracks, HI, as part of its 3rd Brigade Combat Team.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The Catamounts deployed from Schofield Barracks in August 1991 to the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Task Force 4/87 performed peace keeping duties as the USBATT assigned to the Multinational Force & Observers at South Camp near Sharm el Sheikh, Egypt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] In February 1992, after their six-month rotation in the Sinai Desert, they redeployed back to Schofield Barracks.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The Catamounts deployed again for their second real-world mission in 13 months.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] In the aftermath of Hurricane Iniki, a Category 4 storm which made landfall on 11 September 1992, the battalion was sent to Kauai and it effectively provided hurricane relief for immediate needs of the local population.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Assistance had arrived before any requests had been made by the local officials for aid.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] For the next month, following Iniki's decimation of Kauai, the soldiers helped in various capacities and distributed water and MRE's.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The battalion redeployed back to Oahu at the mission's end in October 1992.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The 4th battalion was deactivated at Schofield Barracks and relieved from the 25th Infantry Division effective 15 July 1995.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The lineage of World War II's Company E, 87th Infantry Regiment was redesignated effective 1 May 1987 as HHC, 5th Battalion, 87th Infantry, assigned to the 193rd Infantry Brigade in Panama and activated.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Concurrently the 1st Battalion, 187th Infantry was inactivated and its personnel and equipment were reflagged as 5-87th.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The battalion was relieved from assignment to the inactivating 193d Infantry Brigade on 15 July 1994 and was itself inactivated on 15 September 1999.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] On 20 December 1989 Task Force "Wildcat" (5th Battalion, 87th Infantry) and Task Force "Bayonet" (193rd Infantry Brigade), attacked and seized critical objectives in Panama City for Operation Just Cause.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Alpha Company 5/87th Infantry 193rd Infantry Brigade, Code Name "Jaguars" seized the PDF Engineer complex on Albrook AFB(I know because I was there).
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Each of these objectives lay astride the key lines of communication into the center of Panama city.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] In the days following the initial assault, TF 5-87 conducted stability operations and was involved in the security of the Santa Felipe, Santa Anna, El Marana, and Chorillo sections of the city.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] During the remainder of the operation, TF Wildcat secured key sites in Panama City and reacted to security and civil military tasking.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] 12 December 1992, 2-87th Infantry, with Co A, 1-87th infantry, deployed to Somalia in support of Operation Restore Hope as the first Army units on the ground.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Co A, 1-87 was attached to 2-87 Infantry to comprise TF 2-87.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] TF 2-87 conducted numerous missions, including several air assault operations (such as an airfield seizure in Beledweyne, Somalia), cordon and search operations, ambushes, search and destroy missions and quick reaction force missions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Members of TF 2-87 were first awarded the Combat Infantryman Badge for actions in the Mogadishu suburb of Afgooye in January 1993.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Both 2-87th and 1-87th engaged in numerous running battles with Somali guerrilla fighters all over southern Somalia.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] In February and March 1993, both 2-87th Inf. and 1-87 Inf. went to the aid of 3-14 Inf. and Belgian forces in the southern port city of Kismayo, after fighting erupted between rival factions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Although 1-87th Infantry never deployed to Somalia as a unit, its companies deployed as attachments to other units and participated in numerous missions, including C Co 1-87 (while attached to 2-14th Inf) and the Battle of Mogadishu.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] In September 1994, the 1st Brigade of the 10th Mountain Division, which included 1-87 Infantry, conducted the Army's first Air Assault operation from the deck of a naval vessel, the USS Dwight D.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Eisenhower (CVN-69), in support of Operation Uphold Democracy in Haiti.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] This was the Army's first air operation from a naval vessel since the Doolittle Raid of World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] In the mid-1990s elements of the 87th Infantry trained in Pakistan, Panama, Kyrgyzstan, and Uzbekistan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] In 1999 Co B, 1-87 was deployed to Bosnia-Herzegovina in support of Operation Joint Forge.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Co C, 1-87 completed a similar deployment from October 1998 to March 1999.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] A detachment (3d Platoon) from Co C, 1-87 was attached to the 2d Battalion, 14th Infantry and served as the Quick Reaction Force (QRF) during the Battle of Mogadishu.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The unit never deployed to Somalia as a whole, but all of 1st Battalion was attached to other units while deployed to Somalia, including 2-87 IN, and the 2d Battalion, 14th Infantry.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The 1st Battalion deployed in support of Operation Enduring Freedom from July 2003 to May 2004.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Although originally slotted as a six-month deployment the unit was extended to ten months due to the invasion of Iraq in 2003.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] From 2005 to 2006 1-87 IN deployed to Baghdad, Iraq in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom III-IV.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] 1-87 deployed in 2007–2008 to the northern Kirkuk area of Iraq, near the small city of Hawijah.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The unit was part of the "Surge" and remained in Kirkuk for 15 months in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom VI.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] 1-87 IN deployed to Northern Afghanistan in early 2010 for 13 months.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The unit's mission was to support Operation Enduring Freedom by partnering with ISAF forces to eliminate Taliban and HIG forces and help establish Afghan government influence in the region.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The battalion was tasked with clearing and securing several districts including Aliabad, Char-a-dara, and the City of Kunduz aiding the Afghan security forces in doing so.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] 1-87 was sent to clear the valleys of Shahabuddin, Gortepa, and Dahana-e-Ghuri.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The battalion successfully cleared villages of Taliban presence then established Afghan local police outposts in the newly acquired areas.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] This task took several weeks, starting with securing the district of Aliabad to the south to impede the Talibans ability to reinforce and resupply the Gortepa valley.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] By the end of March 2011, 1-87 had returned to Fort Drum.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Notably, Blacksheep Company was responsible for numerous large-scale engagements, including the Battle of Shahabuddin and securing a High-Value Target (HVT) after an air assault raid.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] This deployment was transformational to the Counterinsurgency in Northern Afghanistan campaign of the war.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] 1-87 IN deployed to Ghazni Province, Afghanistan in 2012 for 12 months.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] 1-87 IN deployed in 2015–2016 with 1st Brigade Combat Team to Iraq in support of Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Charlie company 1-87 IN deployed to Cameroon in August 2017 while the rest of the battalion deployed to Afghanistan in late September of the same year.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] 1-87 IN deployed to Afghanistan in March 2020 with 1st Brigade Combat Team in support of Operation Freedom's Sentinel.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] 1-87 IN deployed to Iraq in May 2022 with 1st Brigade Combat Team in support of Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Alpha company 1-87 IN deployed to Baghdad, Iraq during the 2022 Baghdad clashes.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Constituted 31 July 1918 in the Regular Army as the 87th Infantry and assigned to the 18th Infantry Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Organized September 1918 at Camp Dodge, Iowa from personnel of the 35th Infantry.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Relieved from the 19th Division and demobilized 27 January 1919 at Camp Dodge.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Redesignated 12 May 1942 as the 87th Mountain Infantry Regiment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Regiment (less 1st Battalion) activated 25 May 1942 at Fort Lewis, Washington. assigned to the 10th Mountain Division, 22 February 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Reorganized and Redesignated 87th Mountain Infantry Regiment and assigned to the 10th Mountain Division 6 November 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Inactivated 21 June 1945 at Camp Carson, Colorado.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Redesignated 87th Infantry and assigned to 10th Infantry Division 18 June 1948, allotted to the regular Army 25 June 1948.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Activated 1 July 1948 at Fort Riley, Kansas.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Relieved from the 10th Infantry Division 1 July 1957 and reorganized as the 87th Infantry, a parent regiment under the Combat Arms Regimental System.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] A silver color metal and enamel device 1+1⁄4 inches (3.2 cm) in height overall consisting of a shield blazoned: Azure, on a mountain issuant from base Argent, an ice axe, and ski pole in saltirewise, points to base Proper, a mule shoe, points to base Gules.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] Attached below the shield is a silver scroll inscribed "VIRES MONTESQUE VINCIMUS" in red letters.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The snow-capped mountains is where the organization first received its specialized training and the normal home of mountains troops.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The crossed ski pole and ice axe are symbolic of the tools used by mountain troops and the mule shoe indicates the pack element of the organization.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The 87th Mountain Infantry Regiment was the only organization of its kind indicated by the single red horseshoe.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The distinctive unit insignia was originally approved for the 87th Mountain Infantry Regiment on 21 October 1942.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] It was redesignated for the 87th Infantry Regiment on 13 December 1948.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The coat of arms was originally approved for the 87th Mountain Infantry Regiment on 21 October 1942.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] On 21 May 1956 the symbolism was amended to correct the translation of the motto.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] On 7 December 1964 the coat of arms was amended to change the wording in the blazonry of the shield and to add the crest.
[src:10th-mountain-division/1-87th-infantry] The insignia was amended to correct the translation of the motto and update the description on 26 February 2016.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The **100th Training Division (Leader Development)** (formerly the **100th Infantry Division**) is a division of the United States Army headquartered at Fort Knox, Kentucky.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] It currently serves as a major training command of the United States Army Reserve.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] It has been known as the *"Century Division"* owing to its "100th" designation.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Throughout its long history, the division has taken on numerous roles.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Serving as the **100th Infantry Division** until the 1950s, the division then briefly became the **100th Airborne Division** before becoming the **100th Division (Training)**.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Since this transformation, the division has primarily taken on numerous training roles for other Army units.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] It was originally activated in mid-1918, too late to join the fighting in World War I.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division is best known for its exploits during World War II as the 100th Infantry Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Fighting in the European Theater, the division advanced through France and Germany through the end of the war, fending off heavy German counterattacks along the way.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] World War II would be the only war the division would see active combat in before taking on a role as a training unit.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] On 23 July 1918, the War Department directed the organization of the 100th Division at Camp Bowie, Texas.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] It was intended that the 199th Infantry Brigade would be organized in France from the 56th and 57th Pioneer Infantry Regiments.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 25th Trench Mortar Battery was formed at Camp Stanley, Texas, in August 1918 and was assigned to the 175th Field Artillery Brigade, but never ended up joining.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The organization of the division began in October with the appointment of Colonel William L.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Reed as division chief of staff, but organization never progressed beyond the assignment of the division staff and preliminary preparations for the receipt of Selective Service men.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] After the Armistice of 11 November 1918, the 100th Division was ordered demobilized on 30 November 1918.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 100th Division was reconstituted in the Organized Reserve on 24 June 1921, allotted to the Fifth Corps Area, and assigned to the XV Corps.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division was further allotted to the states of West Virginia and Kentucky as its home area.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division headquarters was organized on 27 September 1921 at 209 Greenbriar Street in Charleston, West Virginia, but relocated in April 1922 to 815 Quarrier Street and moved again in September 1922 to the Morrison Building in Charleston.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] On 29 May 1923, the division received its shoulder sleeve insignia.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The headquarters was relocated a final time on 30 June 1928 from 1313 Union Bank and Trust Building in Charleston to the Coal Exchange Building in Huntington, and remained there until activated for World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] To maintain communications with the officers of the division, the division staff published a newsletter titled “The Century,” which alluded to the division's numerical designation.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 100th Division headquarters occasionally trained with the staff of the 5th Division's 10th Infantry Brigade at Fort Benjamin Harrison, Indiana.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The subordinate infantry regiments of the division held their summer training primarily with the units of the 10th Infantry Brigade at Camp Knox or Fort Thomas, Kentucky, or Fort Benjamin Harrison.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Some years, the division's 167th and 168th Infantry Brigades and their subordinate units conducted camp at the Culver Military Academy in Culver, Indiana.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Other units, such as the special troops, artillery, engineers, aviation, medical, and quartermaster, trained at various posts in the Fifth Corps Areas, usually with active units of the 5th Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In addition to the unit training camps, the infantry regiments of the division rotated responsibility for conducting the infantry CMTC training held at Camp Knox and Fort Thomas each year.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] On a number of occasions, the division participated in Fifth Corps Area and Second Army command post exercises (CPXs) in conjunction with other Regular Army, National Guard, and Organized Reserve units.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] These training events gave division staff officers’ opportunities to practice the roles they would be expected to perform in the event the division was mobilized.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Unlike the Regular and Guard units in the Fifth Corps Area, however, the 100th Division did not participate in the various Fifth Corps Area maneuvers and the Second Army maneuvers of 1936, 1940, and 1941 as an organized unit due to lack of enlisted personnel and equipment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Instead, the officers and a few enlisted reservists were assigned to Regular and Guard units to fill vacant slots and bring the units up to war strength for the exercises.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Additionally, some officers were assigned duties as umpires or as support personnel.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Before Organized Reserve infantry divisions were ordered into active military service, they were reorganized on paper as "triangular" divisions under the 1940 tables of organization.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The headquarters companies of the two infantry brigades were consolidated into the division's cavalry reconnaissance troop, and one infantry regiment was removed by inactivation.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The field artillery brigade headquarters and headquarters battery became the headquarters and headquarters battery of the division artillery.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The engineer, medical, and quartermaster regiments were reorganized into battalions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In 1942, divisional quartermaster battalions were split into ordnance light maintenance companies and quartermaster companies, and the division's headquarters and military police company, which had previously been a combined unit, was split.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] On 15 August 1942, the War Department designated Major General Withers A.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Burress as division commander, Colonel Maurice L.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Miller as assistant division commander, and Colonel Theodore A.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Buechler as division artillery commander.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Miller and Buechler were later promoted to brigadier general.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The officer cadre (regimental, battalion, and company commanders) was designated by the end of August, and was dispatched to training schools to prepare them for their new assignments.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In October 1942, they reported to Fort Jackson, South Carolina, and were joined by about 400 "filler" officers principally obtained from officer candidate schools.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In mid-October, the non-commissioned officer cadre, provided principally by the 76th Infantry Division arrived at Fort Jackson.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 100th Infantry Division was officially ordered into active military service on 15 November 1942.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Basic training began on 28 December 1942.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] From late 1943 to early 1944, the division trained in the mountains of Tennessee and was subsequently sent to Fort Bragg, North Carolina, for further training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] While at Fort Bragg, Technical Sergeant Walter L.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Bull earned the first Expert Infantryman's Badge.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Between January 1943 and August 1944, the division sent 14,636 enlisted men and 1,400 officers as cadres or fillers for other units or to overseas replacement depots.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The latter transfers were to obey two War Department directives issued in January and February 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The first was that the greatest possible proportion of men sent overseas as replacements have at least six months of training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The latter was to prohibit 18 year olds and men with children conceived prior to Pearl Harbor who had less than six months of training from being sent overseas as replacements unless men could be found from other sources.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In June 1944, the age rule became even stricter, with no men under 19 shipped as replacements in infantry or armor under any circumstances, and no men under 18 years and 6 months assigned to infantry or armor replacement training centers.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Between April 1944 ("when the initial age rules began to have a substantial effect") and September 1944 (when the age policy came to an end), the 100th Infantry Division lost 125 infantry noncommissioned officers and 3,859 privates.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division sailed to Europe on 6 October of that year.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division arrived at Marseille, France, on 20 October.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] It was made part of VI Corps of the Seventh United States Army, Sixth United States Army Group.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] As soon as the division was prepared for combat, it began moving into the Meurthe-et-Moselle region, and sent its first elements into combat at St.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Remy in the Vosges Mountains on 1 November 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division as a whole began the relief of the 45th Infantry Division at Baccarat on 5 November, and assumed control of the sector on 9 November.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The attack jumped off on 12 November, and the division drove against the German Winter Line in the Vosges Mountains.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 100th took Bertrichamps and Clairupt, pierced the German line, and seized Raon-l'Étape and Saint-Blaise-Moyenmoutier between 16 and 26 November.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Later in November the division moved into the Vosges region, elements assisted in holding the Saverne Gap bridgehead while the bulk of the division went into reserve.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The unit was relieved from assignment to VI Corps and transferred to the US XV Corps on 27 November 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In December 1944, the division went on the offensive in the vicinity of Bitche, France.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division occupied the nearby areas of Wingen and Lemberg after fierce fighting on 6–10 December.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division then advanced to Reyersviller, which fell after fighting on 11–13 December.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] On 14 December, regiments from the 100th started their assault on a minor fortification Freundenburg and Fort Schiesseck, a major defensive work in the region.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Fort Freundenburg was captured on 17 December by the 100th division's 398th Infantry Regiment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Fort Schiesseck capitulated after three more days of heavy assault by the 100th on 20 December.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division was ordered to halt its attack and to hold defensive positions south of Bitche as part of the Seventh Army during the Battle of the Bulge.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Thanks to a stout defense, the men of the 100th later became known as the "Sons of Bitche".
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The German counterattacks of 1 and 8–10 January 1945 were repulsed, after heavy fighting at Bitche.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] After further attacks stalled and the Germans began to withdraw, the sector was generally quiet and the division prepared to resume its offensive east.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] On 15 March 1945, the attack jumped off and on 16 March, Bitche fell to the 100th Infantry Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The unit was then relieved from assignment to XV Corps, and transferred to XXI Corps on 22 March 1945.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Taking Neustadt and Ludwigshafen, the division reached the Rhine River on 24 March.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] On 25 March 1945, the unit was returned from XXI Corps back to VI Corps.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] On 31 March 1945, the 100th Infantry Division crossed the Rhine and moved south in the wake of the 10th Armored Division and then east across the Neckar River, establishing and enlarging a bridgehead from 4 to 11 April.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Heilbronn fell after nine days of house-to-house combat on 12 April and the division resumed its rapid pursuit of the enemy, reaching Stuttgart by 21 April.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 100th was mopping up along the Neckar, southeast of Stuttgart on 23 April, when it was removed from VI Corps and assigned directly to the Seventh United States Army as an Echelon Above Corps Asset.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division was then assigned primarily to patrolling the sector east of Stuttgart.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Shifting to Göppingen on 30 April, the Division engaged in occupational duties as the war in Europe came to an end on V-E Day.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division had spent 163 days in combat.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division took 13,351 enemy prisoners of war on its own.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Members of the division won three Medals of Honor, seven Distinguished Service Crosses, five Legions of Merit, 492 Silver Star Medals, 23 Soldier's Medals, 5,156 Bronze Star Medals, and 90 Air Medals.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division itself was awarded three campaign streamers for participation in the campaign.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] 100th Infantry Division returned to the United States via the Hampton Roads Port of Embarkation on 10 January 1946, and was released from active duty at Camp Patrick Henry, Virginia that day.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division then began the process of demobilization, before inactivating on 26 January.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In fall of 1946, the division was reactivated in the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Army Reserve as the 100th Airborne Division in Louisville, Kentucky.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] It was assigned to Second United States Army.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] This distinction as one of the few airborne divisions within the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Army was brief; in 1952 the division was once again redesignated the 100th Infantry Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In 1955, it became the 100th Division (Replacement Training).
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In 1959 it became the 100th Division (Institutional Training).
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Its mission became to teach basic, advanced, and common training skills to soldiers from the active Army; the Army Reserve; and the Army National Guard.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In 1961, some 1,500 soldiers from the 100th were activated and sent to Fort Chaffee, Arkansas, in order to provide support during the Berlin Crisis.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] During their time on active duty, the 100th successfully trained some 32,000 soldiers after thoroughly rebuilding and fixing the old Army base.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The unit was returned to reserve status again in August 1962.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division was transferred to First United States Army on 1 January 1966.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In 1968, the division received its distinctive unit insignia, which alluded to its history in World War II and as a Kentucky-based unit.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] With the implementation of the Reorganization Objective Army Division TOE in 1968, the division ceased to be centered on regiments and instead was reorganized with brigades.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] However, with the 199th Infantry Brigade active as a separate brigade, the division's new brigades were activated from units that had been under its command in World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division's headquarters element (which had since been replaced by a Headquarters and Headquarters Company) was redesignated the 1st Brigade, 100th Division responsible for basic armor school training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 928th Field Artillery Battalion became the 2nd Brigade, 100th Division responsible for armored cavalry unit training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 325th Engineer Battalion became the 3rd Brigade, 100th Division responsible for combat support training, and the 800th Ordnance Battalion became the 4th Brigade, 100th Division, responsible for combat service support training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In 1977 the divisional mission changed from basic combat and advanced individual armor training to One Station Unit Training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division had to prepare for mobilization to conduct entry level armor or armoured reconnaissance training for enlistees in one station format.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The next year, the division the first Army Reserve formation to be equipped with its own squadrons of M1 Abrams tanks.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] With the arrival of the M3 Bradley infantry fighting vehicles, the division's mission profile changed from individual combat training to armor and armor reconnaissance training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] By 1986, it was the largest reserve unit within the state of Kentucky, commanding fifty-eight percent of instate reservists.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] At the outbreak of Operation Desert Storm in 1991, the 100th was assigned to armor training at Fort Knox, Kentucky for deploying armor units.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Armor training was a responsibility that the division continued after the war.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In 1995 the division was reorganized to include Army Reserve schools, taking over the responsibilities for new programs.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] In 1996 the 100th Division's 1st Brigade worked with Readiness Group Knox to pioneer the national training experiment to reserve combat units at crew and platoon levels.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 5th Brigade moved to Millington, Tennessee in 1997, and the 7th Brigade inactivated in 2000.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 8th Brigade, 100th Division was also activated as a unit overseeing ROTC training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] During 1997, the division was tasked with partial responsibility for Operation Future Challenge at Fort Knox, a six-week Reserve Officer's Training Corps Basic Camp during each summer.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] By 2000, the 100th has assumed full responsibility for running the camp.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Later that same year, the 100th began inactivating many of its M1A1 Abrams tanks as part of a reduction in military expenditures.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] After the September 11 attacks, the 100th Division began preparing Army National Guard units from Ohio and Kentucky as they prepared for deployment to the War in Afghanistan (2001-2021) and, possibly, the Iraq War (U.S. phase, 2003–2011).
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] By 2006, the division had moved its headquarters from Louisville to Fort Knox, easing distance strains in administration and training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division was restructured, eliminating all but four of its brigades.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division shifted its focus from initial entry training to providing military occupational specialty and non-commissioned officer training for four army career fields across the United States.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 100th Division (Operational Support) teaches soldiers subjects from military intelligence, signal corps, civil affairs/psychological operations and health services.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] On 1 October 2018 the 100th Training Division was redesignated as the 100th Training Division (Leader Development).
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 100th Training Division (Leader Development) establishes and implements the Army Reserve Leader Development Strategy to provide a continuum of career education, training, and experience for leaders in the Army Reserve.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] During this reorganization, the 83rd USARRTC and the 97th (CGSOC) Brigade were placed under the 100th Training Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The 100th Training Division (Operational Support) is a subordinate unit of the 80th Training Command (The Army School System — TASS).
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The division's legacy in World War II has been honored several times.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] The Cross Island Parkway in Queens, New York was renamed the "100th Infantry Division Parkway" in 2005 in honor of 2,300 soldiers from New York that served with the division during the war.
[src:10th-mountain-division/100th-infantry-division-united-states] Three soldiers earned the Medal of Honor serving with the division in World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] The **101st Airborne Division (Air Assault)** ("Screaming Eagles") is a light infantry division of the United States Army that specializes in air assault operations.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] The 101st is designed to plan, coordinate, and execute brigade-sized air assault operations that can be conducted in one period of darkness, at distances up to 500 nautical miles (926 kilometers), to seize key terrain and hold it for up to 14 days.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] In recent years, the 101st was active in security force assistance and counterinsurgency operations in Iraq, in Afghanistan in 2015–2016, and in Syria, as part of Operation Inherent Resolve in 2018–2021.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] Established in 1918, the 101st Division was first constituted as an airborne unit in 1942.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] During World War II, it gained renown for its role in Operation Overlord (the D-Day landings and airborne landings on 6 June 1944, in Normandy, France); Operation Market Garden; the liberation of the Netherlands; and its action during the Battle of the Bulge around the city of Bastogne, Belgium.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] During the Vietnam War, the 101st Airborne Division fought in several major campaigns and battles, including the Battle of Hamburger Hill in 1969 and the Battle of Fire Support Base Ripcord in 1970.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] In mid-1968, the division was reorganized and redesignated as an airmobile division and in 1974, the division was again redesigned as an air assault division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] The titles reflect the division's shift from airplanes to helicopters as the primary method of delivering troops into combat.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] At the height of the war on terrorism, the 101st Airborne Division (Air Assault) had over 200 aircraft.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] This shrank to just over 100 aircraft with the inactivation of the 159th Combat Aviation Brigade in 2015.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] In 2019, media reports suggested the Army was working to restore the 101st's aviation capabilities so it can return to lifting an entire brigade in one air assault.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] The 101st's headquarters is at Fort Campbell, Kentucky.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] Many members of the 101st are graduates of the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] Army Air Assault School, which is co-located with the division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] The school is known as one of the Army's most difficult courses; only about half of those who begin it will graduate.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] The Screaming Eagles were referred to as "the tip of the spear" by former U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p01] Secretary of Defense, Robert Gates, and the most potent and tactically mobile of the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] On 23 July 1918, the War Department directed the organization of the 101st Division in the National Army at Camp Shelby, Mississippi, under the supervision of camp commander Brigadier General Roy Hoffman.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] It was intended that the 201st Infantry Brigade would be organized in France from the 58th and 59th Pioneer Infantry Regiments.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 27th Trench Mortar Battery was formed at Camp Bowie, Texas, in August 1918 and was assigned to the 176th Field Artillery Brigade, but never ended up joining.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The organization of the division began in October and Colonel Patrick H.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Mullay was named division chief of staff on 2 November, but organization never progressed beyond the formation of the division headquarters and preliminary preparations for the receipt of Selective Service men.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] After the Armistice of 11 November 1918, the 101st Division was ordered demobilized on 30 November 1918, being completed on 11 December.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In 1921, pursuant to the National Defense Act of 1920, the 101st Division was reconstituted in the Organized Reserve, allotted to the Sixth Corps Area, and assigned to the XVI Corps, and further allotted to the state of Wisconsin.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The division headquarters was organized on 10 September 1921 in Room 412 of the Federal Building in Milwaukee, moving in July 1922 to the Pereles Building, where it remained until activated for World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The designated mobilization and training station for the division was Camp Custer, Michigan, where much of the division's annual training activities occurred in the interwar years.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The headquarters and staff usually trained with the staff of the 12th Infantry Brigade either at Camp Custer or Fort Sheridan, Illinois, while the infantry regiments trained primarily with the 2nd Infantry Regiment at Camp Custer.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The special troops, artillery, engineers, aviation, medical, and quartermaster units trained at various posts in the Sixth and Seventh Corps Areas.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In addition, division personnel also conducted the Citizens' Military Training Camps in the division's home area as an alternate form of annual training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The division's primary "feeder" schools for newly commissioned Reserve lieutenants were the University of Wisconsin, Ripon College, and St.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Instead, the officers and a few enlisted reservists were assigned to Regular Army and National Guard units to fill vacant slots, and some officers were assigned duties as umpires or support personnel.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] It was at this time that the "Screaming Eagle" mascot became associated with the division, as a successor to the traditions of the Wisconsin volunteer regiments of the American Civil War.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] On 30 July 1942, the Army Ground Forces ordered the activation of two airborne divisions by 15 August 1942.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 82nd Division, an Organized Reserve division ordered into active military service in March 1942, was ordered to provide cadre to the 101st Division, the other division that was selected for the project, for all elements except parachute infantry.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] As part of the reorganization of the 101st Division as an airborne division, the unit was disbanded in the Organized Reserve on 15 August 1942 and reconstituted and reactivated in the Army of the United States.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] On 19 August 1942, its first commander, Major General William C.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The pathfinders of the 101st Airborne Division led the way on D-Day in the night drop before the invasion.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] They left from RAF North Witham, having trained there with the 82nd Airborne Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] These night drops caused a lot of trouble for the gliders.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Many crashed and equipment and personnel were lost.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st Airborne Division's objectives were to secure the four causeway exits behind Utah Beach between Saint-Martin-de-Varreville and Pouppeville to ensure the exit route for the 4th Infantry Division from the beach later that morning.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Their secondary mission was to protect the southern flank of VII Corps.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] They destroyed two bridges along the Carentan highway and a railroad bridge just west of it.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] They gained control of La Barquette locks, and established a bridgehead over the Douve which was located north-east of Carentan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The paratroopers of the 101st Airborne Division jumped between 00:48 and 01:40 British Double Summer Time of 6 June.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The first wave, inbound to Drop Zone A (the northernmost), was not surprised by the cloud bank and maintained formation, but navigating errors and a lack of Eureka signal caused the first error.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Although the 2nd Battalion, 502nd Parachute Infantry Regiment was dropped as a compact unit, it jumped on the wrong drop zone, while its commander, Lt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Chappuis, came down virtually alone on the correct drop zone.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Chappuis and his paratrooper captured the coastal battery soon after assembling, and found that it had already been dismantled after an air raid.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Most of the remainder of the 502nd (70 of 80 paratroopers) dropped in a disorganized pattern around the impromptu drop zone set up by the pathfinders near the beach.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The battalion commanders of the 1st and 3rd Battalions, Lt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Cole (3/502), took charge of small groups and accomplished all of their D-Day missions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Cassidy's group took Saint Martin-de-Varreville by 06:30, sent a patrol under S/Sgt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Summers to seize the "XYZ" objective, a barracks at Mésières, and set up a thin line of defense from Foucarville to Beuzeville.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Cole's group moved during the night from near Sainte-Mère-Église to the Varreville battery, then continued on and captured Exit 3 at 07:30.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] They held the position during the morning until relieved by troops moving inland from Utah Beach.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Both commanders found Exit 4 covered by German artillery fire and Cassidy recommended to the 4th Infantry Division that it not use the exit.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The division's parachute artillery did not fare nearly as well.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Its drop was one of the worst of the operation, losing all but one howitzer and dropping all but two of 54 loads four to twenty miles (32 km) to the north, where most ultimately became casualties.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The second wave, assigned to drop the 506th Parachute Infantry Regiment (PIR) on Drop Zone C 1 mile (1.6 km) west of Sainte Marie-du-Mont, was badly dispersed by the clouds, then subjected to intense anti-aircraft fire for 10 miles (16 km).
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Three of the 81 C-47s were lost before or during the jump.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Muir of the 439th Troop Carrier Group, caught fire.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Muir held the aircraft steady while the stick jumped, then died when the plane crashed immediately afterward, for which he was awarded the Distinguished Service Cross.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Despite the opposition, the 506th's 1st Battalion (the original division reserve) was dropped accurately on DZ C, landing two-thirds of its sticks and regimental commander Col.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Sink on or within a mile of the drop zone.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Most of the 2nd Battalion had jumped too far west, near Sainte-Mère-Église.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] They eventually assembled near Foucarville at the northern edge of the 101st Airborne's objective area.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] It fought its way to the hamlet of Le Grand Chemin near the Houdienville causeway by mid-afternoon, but found that the 4th Division had already seized the exit hours before.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 3rd Battalion of the 501st PIR, led by Lt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Ewell (3/501), also assigned to jump onto DZ C, was more scattered, but took over the mission of securing the exits.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] An ad hoc company-sized team that included division commander Maj.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Taylor reached the Pouppeville exit at 06:00.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] After a six-hour house-clearing battle with elements of the German 1058th Grenadier Regiment, the group secured the exit shortly before 4th Division troops arrived to link up.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The third wave also encountered severe flak, losing six aircraft.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The troop carriers still made an accurate drop, placing 94 of 132 sticks on or close to the drop zone, but part of the DZ was covered by pre-registered German machine gun and mortar fire that inflicted heavy casualties before many troops could get out of their chutes.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Among the killed were two of the three battalion commanders and the executive officer of the 3/506th.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Ballard, gathered 250 troopers and advanced toward Saint Côme-du-Mont to complete his mission of destroying the highway bridges over the Douve.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Less than half a mile from his objective at les Droueries he was stopped by elements of battalion III/1058 Grenadier-Rgt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Another group of 50 men, assembled by the regimental S-3, Major Richard J.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Allen, attacked the same area from the east at Basse-Addeville but was also pinned down.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Johnson, collected 150 troops and captured the main objective, la Barquette lock, by 04:00.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] After establishing defensive positions, Col.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Johnson went back to the DZ and assembled another 100 men, including Allen's group, to reinforce the bridgehead.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Despite naval gunfire support from the cruiser *Quincy*, Ballard's battalion was unable to take Saint Côme-du-Mont or join Col.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The S-3 officer of the 3rd Battalion 506th PIR, Capt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Shettle, put together a platoon and achieved another objective by seizing two foot bridges near la Porte at 04:30 and crossed to the east bank.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] When their ammunition drew low after knocking out several machine gun emplacements, the small force withdrew to the west bank.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] It doubled in size overnight as stragglers came in and repulsed a German probe across the bridges.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Two other noteworthy actions took place near Sainte Marie-du-Mont by units of the 506th PIR, both of which involved the seizure and destruction of batteries of 105 mm guns of the German III Battalion-191st Artillery Regiment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] During the morning, a small patrol of troopers from Company E 506th PIR under (then) 1st Lt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Winters overwhelmed a force 3–4 times its size and destroyed four guns at a farm called Brécourt Manor, for which Winters was later awarded the Distinguished Service Cross and the assault troops given Silver and Bronze Stars.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Around noon, while reconnoitering the area by jeep, Col.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Sink received word that a second battery of four guns had been discovered at Holdy, a manor between his CP and Sainte Marie-du-Mont, and the defenders had a force of some 70 paratroopers pinned down.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Patch (Headquarters Company 1st/506th) and Capt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Raudstein (Company C 506th PIR) led an additional 70 troops to Holdy and enveloped the position.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The combined force then continued on to seize Sainte Marie-du-Mont.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] A platoon of the 502nd PIR, left to hold the battery, destroyed three of the four guns before Col.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Sink could send four jeeps to save them for the 101st's use.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Taylor and division artillery commander Brig.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] McAuliffe returned from their foray at Pouppeville.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Taylor had control of approximately 2,500 of his 6,600 men, most of whom were in the vicinity of the 506th CP at Culoville, with the thin defense line west of Saint Germain-du-Varreville, or the division reserve at Blosville.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Two glider airlifts had brought in scant reinforcements and had resulted in the death of his assistant division commander (ADC), Brig.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 327th Glider Infantry had come across Utah Beach but only its third battalion (1st Battalion 401st GIR) had reported in.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st Airborne Division had accomplished its most important mission of securing the beach exits, but had a tenuous hold on positions near the Douve River, over which the Germans could still move armored units.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The three groups clustered there had tenuous contact with each other but none with the rest of the division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] A shortage of radio equipment caused by losses during the drops exacerbated his control problems.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Taylor made destroying the Douve bridges the division's top priority and delegated the task to Sink, who issued orders for the 1st Battalion 401st Glider Infantry to lead three battalions south the next morning.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] On 10 June the division launched an assault to seize the town of Carentan, a major road and rail hub that served as a critical junction between Utah and Omaha beaches.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] As such Carentan was heavily defended by the 2nd Fallschirmjäger-Division, 91st Luftlande-Infanterie-Division and elements of the 17th SS Panzergrenadier Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Deliberate flooding of the Douve River floodplain north of the town left the elevated causeway linking Saint-Côme-du-Mont and Carentan, later named Purple Heart Lane, as the most expedient route to Carentan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 502nd PIR was assigned the task of assaulting down this highway while the 327th GIR crossed the Douve north of Carentan and attacked from the northeast.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] 3rd Battalion, 502nd PIR led the 502nds attack, with a reconnaissance patrol reaching the fourth and final bridge on the causeway into Carentan on the morning of 10 June.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The rest of 3/502 attempted to reach the fourth bridge during the day, but damage to the preceding bridges on the causeway, as well as artillery, dive bomber, machine gun and sniper fire, stalled the battalion until the next day and inflicted heavy casualties.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Early on 11 June, 3/502 resumes its attack and attempts to seize a farmhouse just beyond Bridge No.4, but is halted by heavy German fire.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Using a smoke screen, the 3/502nd's battalion commander, Lieutenant Colonel Robert G.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Cole, led a bayonet charge that secured the farmhouse, allowing the 506th PIR to pass the 502nds lines and seize Carentan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] For his bravery and leadership, LTC Cole was awarded the first of two Medals of Honor earned by Screaming Eagle soldiers in WWII.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] By D plus 8, 14 June, the mop up of scattered enemy resistance was in its final stages.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 327th GIR maintained a defensive posture along the railway from Carentan on the right to the crossing of the Vire River on the left.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 506th Parachute Infantry was ordered to prepare a strong reserve defensive position just west and southwest of Carentan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] On the 15th, troops of the 30th Division passed through the 327th positions while the 29th linked up and consolidated one flank of the 101st positions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] On the 16th the 327th took up defensive positions between the 502nd and the 501st.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] As the regular troops moved in from the beachheads including those of the 83rd Division, strengthening the paratrooper positions, the 101st was relieved and returned to England to rest and refit for the next airborne operation.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The first elements of the division returned to Southampton, England on 12 July 1944 in the presence of Secretary of War Henry L.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Stimson according to the private papers of Lt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Lee, commanding general of the Communications Zone, ETO who received the Secretary's visit.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] After the American breakout from Normandy and subsequent liberation of France, SHAEF planned several jumps for the 101st ahead of the advancing armies, but all were cancelled prior to launch due to the rapid advance of Allied ground troops.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] On 17 September 1944, the 101st Airborne Division became part of XVIII Airborne Corps, under Major General Matthew Ridgway, part of the First Allied Airborne Army, commanded by Lieutenant General Lewis H.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The division took part in Operation Market Garden (17–25 September 1944), an unsuccessful Allied military operation under Field Marshal Bernard Montgomery, commander of the Anglo-Canadian 21st Army Group, to capture Dutch bridges over the Rhine.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] It was fought in the Netherlands, and is the largest airborne operation of any war.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The plan, as outlined by Montgomery, required the seizure by airborne forces of several bridges on the Highway 69 across the Maas (Meuse River) and two arms of the Rhine (the Waal and the Lower Rhine), as well as several smaller canals and tributaries.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Crossing these bridges would allow British armoured units to outflank the Siegfried Line, advance into northern Germany, and encircle the Ruhr, Germany's industrial heartland, thus ending the war.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] This meant the large-scale use of Allied airborne forces, including both the 82nd and 101st Airborne Divisions, along with the British 1st Airborne Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Several bridges between Eindhoven and Nijmegen were captured by the 82nd and 101st.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st met little resistance and captured most of their initial objectives by the end of 17 September.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] However, the demolition of the division's primary objective, a bridge over the Wilhelmina Canal at Son, delayed the capture of the main road bridge over the Maas until 20 September.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Faced with the loss of the bridge at Son, the 101st unsuccessfully attempted to capture a similar bridge a few kilometers away at Best but found the approach blocked.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] During the fighting near Best, Private First Class Joe E.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Mann of 3rd Battalion, 502nd PIR posthumously earned the division's second and last Medal of Honor during WWII for throwing his body unto a German grenade he was too badly wounded to throw back, saving several of his fellow soldiers.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Other units continued moving to the south and eventually reached the northern end of Eindhoven.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] At 06:00 on 18 September, the Irish Guards of the British Guards Armoured Division resumed the advance while facing determined resistance from German infantry and tanks.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Around noon the 101st Airborne were met by the lead reconnaissance units from British XXX Corps.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] At 16:00 radio contact alerted the main force that the Son bridge had been destroyed and requested that a replacement Bailey bridge be brought forward.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] By nightfall the Guards Armoured Division had established itself in the Eindhoven area however transport columns were jammed in the packed streets of the town and were subjected to German aerial bombardment during the night.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] XXX Corps engineers, supported by German prisoners of war, constructed a class 40 Bailey bridge within 10 hours across the Wilhelmina Canal.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The longest sector of the highway secured by the 101st Airborne Division later became known as "Hell's Highway".
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Due to Operation Market Garden significantly extending the 21st Army Groups line, the 101st was attached to 21st Army Group to prevent its lines from being undermanned.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st reinforced the Nijmegen salient and relieved the British 43rd Wessex Division to defend against the German counter offensive against the salient in early October.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The division was relieved in late November 1944 and returned to SHAEF reserve for rest and refit.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The Ardennes Offensive (16 December 1944 – 25 January 1945) was a major German offensive launched towards the end of World War II through the forested Ardennes Mountains region of Belgium.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Germany's planned goal for these operations was to split the British and American Allied line in half, capturing Antwerp, Belgium in the process, and then proceeding to encircle and destroy the entire British 21st Army Group and all 12th U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Army Group units north of the German advance, forcing the Western Allies to negotiate a peace treaty in the Axis Powers' favor as a result.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In order to reach Antwerp before the Allies could regroup and bring their superior air power to bear, German mechanized forces had to seize all the major highways through eastern Belgium.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Because all seven of the main roads in the Ardennes converged on the small town of Bastogne, control of its crossroads was vital to the success or failure of the German attack.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Despite several notable signs in the weeks preceding the attack, the Ardennes Offensive achieved virtually complete surprise.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] By the end of the second day of battle, it became apparent that the 28th Infantry Division was near collapse.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Middleton, commander of VIII Corps, ordered part of his armored reserve, Combat Command B of the 10th Armored Division to Bastogne.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Eisenhower ordered forward the SHAEF reserve, composed of the 82nd and 101st Airborne, which were stationed at Reims.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Both divisions were alerted on the evening of 17 December, and not having organic transport, began arranging trucks for movement forward, the weather conditions being unfit for a parachute drop.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 82nd, longer in reserve and thus better re-equipped, moved out first.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st left Camp Mourmelon on the afternoon of 18 December, with the order of march the division artillery, division trains, 501st PIR, 506th PIR, 502nd PIR, and 327th Glider Infantry.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Much of the convoy was conducted at night in drizzle and sleet, using headlights despite threat of air attack to speed the movement, and at one point the combined column stretched from Bouillon, Belgium, back to Reims.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st Airborne was routed to Bastogne, located 107 miles (172 km) away on a 1,463 feet (446 m) high plateau, while the 82nd Airborne took up positions further north to block the critical advance of *Kampfgruppe Peiper* toward Werbomont, Belgium.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 705th Tank Destroyer Battalion, in reserve sixty miles to the north, was ordered to Bastogne to provide anti-tank support to the armorless 101st Airborne on the 18th and arrived late the next evening.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The first elements of the 501st PIR entered the division assembly area four miles west of Bastogne shortly after midnight of 19 December, and by 09:00 the entire division had arrived.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] By 21 December, the German forces had surrounded Bastogne, which was defended by both the 101st Airborne and Combat Command B of the 10th Armored Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Conditions inside the perimeter were tough—most of the medical supplies and medical personnel had been captured on 19 December.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Three artillery battalions, including the all-black 969th Field Artillery Battalion, were commandeered by the 101st and formed a temporary artillery group.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Each had twelve 155 mm howitzers, providing the division with heavy firepower in all directions restricted only by its limited ammunition supply (by 22 December artillery ammunition was restricted to 10 rounds per gun per day).
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The weather cleared the next day, however, and supplies (primarily ammunition) were dropped over four of the next five days.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Despite several determined German attacks, the perimeter held.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The German commander, Generalleutnant Heinrich Freiherr von Lüttwitz, requested Bastogne's surrender.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] When General Anthony McAuliffe, now acting commander of the 101st, was told, he commented : "Nuts!" After turning to other pressing issues, his staff reminded him that there should be a reply to the German demand.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Kinnard, then a lieutenant colonel) recommended that McAuliffe's reply would be "tough to beat".
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Thus, McAuliffe wrote on the paper delivered to the Germans: "NUTS!" That reply had to be explained, both to the Germans and to non-American Allies.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Both of the two panzer divisions of the XLVII Panzer Corps moved forward from Bastogne after 21 December, leaving only one panzergrenadier regiment of the Panzer-Lehr-Division to assist the 26th Volksgrenadier Division in attempting to capture the crossroads.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 26th VG received additional armor and panzergrenadier reinforcements on Christmas Eve to prepare for its final assault, to take place on Christmas Day.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Because it lacked sufficient armor and troops and the 26th VG Division was near exhaustion, the XLVII Panzer Corps concentrated the assault on several individual locations on the west side of perimeter in sequence rather than launching one simultaneous attack on all sides.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The assault, despite initial success by German tanks in penetrating the American line, was defeated and virtually all of the German tanks involved were destroyed.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The next day, 26 December, the spearhead of General George S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Third Army relief force, the 4th Armored Division, broke through the German lines and opened a corridor to Bastogne, ending the siege.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The division got the nickname "The Battered Bastards of the Bastion of Bastogne".
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] With the encirclement broken, the men of the 101st expected to be relieved, but were given orders to resume the offensive.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 506th attacked north and recaptured Recogne on 9 January 1945, the Bois des Corbeaux (*Corbeaux Wood*), to the right of Easy Company, on 10 January, and Foy on 13 January.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 327th attacked towards Bourcy, northeast of Bastogne, on 13 January and encountered stubborn resistance.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st Airborne Division faced the elite of the German military which included such units as 1st SS Panzer Division Leibstandarte SS Adolf Hitler, Führerbegleitbrigade, 12th SS Panzer Division Hitlerjugend, and the 9th SS Panzer Division Hohenstaufen.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 506th retook Noville on 15 January and Rachamps the next day.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 502nd reinforced the 327th, and the two regiments captured Bourcy on 17 January, pushing the Germans back to their point of advance on the day the division had arrived in Bastogne.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The next day the 101st Airborne Division was relieved.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In April 1945, the 101st moved into the Rhineland and eventually reached the Bavarian Alps.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] As the 101st drove into Southern Germany they liberated Kaufering IV, one of the camps in the Kaufering complex.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Kaufering IV had been designated as the sick camp where prisoners who could no longer work were sent.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] During the typhus epidemic of 1945 in Germany, Kaufering prisoners with typhus were sent there to die.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Kaufering IV was located near the town of Hurlach, which the 12th Armored Division occupied on 27 April, with the 101st arriving the next day.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The soldiers found over 500 dead inmates and the Army ordered the local townspeople to bury the dead.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] When Taylor asked "We've licked the best that Hitler had in France and Holland and Germany.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Now where do we want to go?" his men shouted "Home", part of the demand among soldiers and civilians for rapid demobilization of United States Armed Forces after World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] On 1 August 1945, the 501st PIR was moved to France, while the rest of the division was based around Zell am See and Kaprun in the Austrian Alps.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Some units within the division began training for redeployment to the Pacific Theatre of War, but the war ended before they were needed.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The division was inactivated 30 November 1945.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] For their efforts during World War II, the 101st Airborne Division was awarded four campaign streamers and two Presidential Unit Citations.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st was distinguished partly by its tactical helmet insignia.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Card suits (diamonds, spades, hearts, and clubs) on each side of the helmet denoted the regiment to which a soldier belonged.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The only exception was the 187th which was added to the division later.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Divisional headquarters and support units were denoted by use of a square and divisional artillery by a circle.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Tick marks at 3, 6, and 9 o'clock indicated to which battalion the individual belonged, while the tick mark at 12 o'clock indicated a headquarters or headquarters company assignment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st Airborne was allotted to the Regular Army in June 1948 and reactivated as a training unit at Camp Breckenridge, Kentucky the following July, only to be inactivated the next year.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] It was reactivated in 1950 following the outbreak of the Korean War, again to serve as a Training Center at Camp Breckenridge until inactivated in December 1953.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] During this time it included the 53rd Airborne Infantry Regiment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] It was reactivated again in May 1954 at Fort Jackson, South Carolina and in March 1956, the 101st was transferred, less personnel and equipment, to Fort Campbell, Kentucky, to be reorganized as a combat division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Using the personnel and equipment of the 187th ARCT and the 508th ARCT, the 101st was reactivated as the first "pentomic" division with five battle groups in place of its World War II structure that included regiments and battalions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Other supporting units were also assigned.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The "Little Rock Nine" were a group of African-American students who were enrolled in Little Rock Central High School in September 1957, as a result of the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Supreme Court's ruling in the historic *Brown v.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Elements of the division's 1st Airborne Battle Group, 327th Infantry were ordered to Little Rock by President Eisenhower to escort the students into the formerly segregated school during the crisis.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The division was under the command of Major General Edwin Walker, who was committed to protecting the black students.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The troops were deployed from September until Thanksgiving 1957, when Task Force 153rd Infantry, (federalized Arkansas Army National Guard) which had also been on duty at the school since 24 September, assumed the responsibility.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In 1958 the US Army formed the Strategic Army Corps consisting of the 101st and 82nd Airborne Divisions and the 1st and 4th Infantry Divisions with a mission of rapid deployment on short notice.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] From 1965 to 1967, the 1st Brigade operated independently as sort of a fire brigade and earned the reputation as being called the "Nomads of Vietnam." They fought in every area of South Vietnam from the Demilitarized Zone up north all the way down the Central Highlands.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In May 1967 the 1st Brigade operated as part of Task Force Oregon.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Within the United States, the 101st, along with the 82nd Airborne Division, was sent in to quell the 1967 Detroit riot.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The rest of the 101st was deployed to Vietnam in November 1967 and the 1st Brigade rejoined its parent division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st was deployed in the northern I Corps region, operating against the People's Army of Vietnam (PAVN) infiltration routes through Laos and the A Shau Valley for most of the war.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Notable among these were the Battle of Hamburger Hill in 1969 and Firebase Ripcord in 1970.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Tiger Force was the nickname of a long-range reconnaissance patrol unit of the 1st Battalion (Airborne), 327th Infantry Regiment, 1st Brigade (Separate), 101st Airborne Division, which fought in the Vietnam War.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The platoon-sized unit, approximately 45 paratroopers, was founded by Colonel David Hackworth in November 1965 to "outguerrilla the guerrillas".
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Tiger Force (Recon) 1/327th was a highly decorated small unit in Vietnam, and paid for its reputation with heavy casualties.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In October 1968, Tiger Force's parent battalion was awarded the Presidential Unit Citation by President Lyndon B.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Johnson, which included a mention of Tiger Force's service at Đắk Tô in June 1966.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The unit was accused of committing multiple war crimes.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Investigators concluded that many of the war crimes indeed took place.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Despite this, the Army decided not to pursue any prosecutions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] By the end of the war, Tiger Force had killed approximately 1,000 enemy soldiers.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In 1971, elements of the division supported Operation Lam Son 719, the South Vietnamese invasion of southern Laos, but only aviation units actually entered Laos.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The division began withdrawing from South Vietnam on 15 May 1971 with the departure of the 3rd Battalion, 506th Infantry.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Most major units of the Division had redeployed by January 1972.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In the seven years that all or part of the division served in Vietnam it suffered 4,011 killed and 18,259 wounded in action.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The division, during this time, participated in 12 separate campaigns and 17 of the division's Medal of Honor recipients are from this period of time – all this giving the 101st Airborne Division a combat record unmatched by any other division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In 1968, the 101st took on the structure and equipment of an airmobile division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Following its return from Vietnam, the division was rebuilt with one brigade (3d) and supporting elements on jump status, using the assets of what had been the 173rd Airborne Brigade.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The remaining two brigades and supporting units were organized as airmobile.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] With the exception of certain specialized units, such as the pathfinders and parachute riggers, in early 1974 the Army terminated jump status for the division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Concurrently the 101st introduced the Airmobile Badge (renamed later that year as the Air Assault Badge), the design of which was based on the Glider Badge of World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Initially the badge was only authorized for wear while assigned to the division, but in 1978 the Army authorized it for service-wide wear.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Soldiers continued to wear the garrison cap with glider patch, bloused boots, and their specific unit's airborne background trimming behind their Air Assault or Parachute Badge, as had division paratroopers before them.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] A blue beret was authorized for the division in March or April 1974 and worn until revoked at the end of 1979.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The division also was authorized to wear a full color (white eagle) shoulder patch insignia instead of the subdued green eagle shoulder patch that was worn as a combat patch by soldiers who fought with the 101st in Vietnam.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] While serving with the 101st, it was also acceptable to wear a non-subdued patch as a combat patch, a distinction shared with the 1st and 5th Infantry divisions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In the late 1970s, the division maintained one battalion on a rotating basis as the division ready force (DRF).
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The force was in place to respond to alerts for action anywhere in the world.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] After alert notification, troopers of the "hot" platoon/company, would be airborne, "wheels-up" within 30 minutes as the first responding unit.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] All other companies of the battalion would follow within one hour.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Within 24 hours there would be one brigade deployed to the affected area, with the remainder of the division deploying as needed.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In September 1980, 1st Battalion, 502nd Infantry, 2nd Brigade, took part in Operation Bright Star '80, an exercise deployment to Egypt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In 1984, the command group formed a full-time team, the "Screaming Eagles", Command Parachute Demonstration Team.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] However the team traces its history to the late 1950s, during the infancy of precision free fall.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] On 12 December 1985, a civilian aircraft, Arrow Air Flight 1285, chartered to transport some of the division from peacekeeping duty with the Multinational Force and Observers on the Sinai Peninsula to Kentucky, crashed just a short distance from Gander International Airport, Gander, Newfoundland.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] All eight air crew members and 248 US servicemen died, most were from the 3d Battalion, 502d Infantry.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] A minority report stated that the accident could have been caused by an onboard explosion of unknown origin prior to impact.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] At the time it was 17th most disastrous aviation accident in terms of fatalities.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] President Ronald Reagan and his wife Nancy traveled to Fort Campbell to comfort grieving family members.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Army Blackhawk helicopters assigned to the 101st Aviation Brigade collided while on a night training mission at Fort Campbell.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The dead included four helicopter crewmen and 13 members of the 502d Infantry Regiment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The Army's accident investigation attributed the crash to pilot error, aircraft design, and the limited field of view afforded pilots using night vision goggles (NVGs).
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Numerous improvements have been made in NVG technology since the accident occurred.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In 1974, the 101st Airborne was reorganized as an air assault division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The foundation of modern-day air assault operations was laid by the German Army's development of air mobility during World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Specifically, the Fallschirmjäger, Brandenburgers, and the 22nd Air Landing Division played key roles in refining these tactics.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Army quickly adopted this concept of offensive operations initially utilizing wooden gliders before the development of helicopters.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Air Assault operations consist of highly mobile teams covering extensive distances and engaging enemy forces behind enemy lines and often by surprise, as they are usually masked by darkness.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st Airborne had earned a place in the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] This doctrine is based on belief that initiative, depth, agility, and synchronization successfully complete a mission.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] First all soldiers are encouraged to take the initiative to seize and exploit opportunities to gain advantages over the enemy.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Second, commanders are urged to utilize the entire depth of the battlefield and strike at rear targets that support frontline enemy troops.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Third, agility requires commanders to strike the enemy quickly where most vulnerable and to respond to the enemy's strengths.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Fourth, synchronization calls for the commander to maximize available combined arms firepower for critical targets to achieve the greatest effect.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] On 17 January 1991, the 101st Aviation Regiment fired the first shots of the war when eight AH-64 helicopters successfully destroyed two Iraqi early warning radar sites.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] In February 1991, the 101st once again had its "Rendezvous with Destiny" in Iraq during the combat air assault into enemy territory.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st Airborne Division struck 155 miles (249 km) behind enemy lines.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] It was the deepest air assault operation in history.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] Approximately 400 helicopters transported 2,000 soldiers into Iraq, where they destroyed Iraqi columns trying to flee westward and prevented the escape of Iraqi forces.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The Screaming Eagles would travel an additional 50–60 miles (80–97 km) into Iraq.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] By nightfall, the 101st had cut off Highway 8, which was a vital supply line running between Basra and the Iraqi forces.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p02] The 101st lost 16 soldiers in action during the 100-hour war and captured thousands of the enemy.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The division has supported humanitarian relief efforts in Rwanda and Somalia, then later supplied peacekeepers to Haiti and Bosnia.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] From February through August 2000, 3rd Brigade 1/187 deployed to Kosovo for peacekeeping operations as part of Task Force Falcon in support of Operation Joint Guardian.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] In August 2000, the 2nd Battalion, 327th Infantry Regiment, as well as some elements from the 502nd Infantry Regiment, helped secure the peace in Kosovo and support the October elections for the formation of the new Kosovo government.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] They were replaced in February 2001 with 2nd Battalion, 502nd Infantry Regiment along with 2nd Brigade HQ and elements of 3rd Battalion.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] In September and October 2000, the 3rd Battalion, 327th Infantry Regiment, helped fight fires on the Bitterroot National Forest in Montana.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Designated Task Force Battle Force and commanded by Lt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Lehr, the battalion fought fires throughout the surrounding areas of their Valley Complex near Darby, Montana.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 101st Airborne (Air Assault) Division brigade performed counterinsurgency operations within Afghanistan, consisting mostly of raids, ambushes and patrolling.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 101st also performed combat air assaults throughout the operation.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 2nd Brigade, "Strike", built around the 502nd Infantry, was largely deployed to Kosovo on peacekeeping operations, with some elements of 3rd Battalion, 502nd, deploying after 9/11 as a security element in the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] CENTCOM AOR with the Fort Campbell-based 5th Special Forces Group.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] They had been positioned in Jordan providing security for 5th SF Group's exercise prior to 9/11.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The division quickly deployed its 3rd Brigade, the 187th Infantry's *Rakkasans*, as the first conventional unit to fight as part of Operation Enduring Freedom.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] After an intense period of combat in rugged Shoh-I-Khot Mountains of eastern Afghanistan during Operation Anaconda with elements of the 10th Mountain Division, the *Rakkasans* redeployed to Fort Campbell only to find the 101st awaiting another deployment order.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] In 2008, the 101st 4th BCT Red and White "Currahee" including the 1st and the 2nd Battalions, 506th Infantry were deployed to Afghanistan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Elements of 1st Battalion, 506th Infantry Regiment participated in joint operations with U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Army Special Forces particularly in the Northern province of Kapisa in the outpost Forward Operating Base (FOB) Kutchsbach.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Charlie Company, 2nd Battalion, 506th Infantry Regiment performed joint operations with 5th Special Forces Group and 20th Special Forces Group in 2011.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 101st Combat Aviation Brigade deployed to Afghanistan as Task Force Destiny in early 2008 to Bagram Air Base.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] 159th Combat Aviation Brigade deployed as Task Force Thunder for 12 months in early 2009, and again in early 2011.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] In March 2010, the 101st Combat Aviation Brigade deployed again to Afghanistan as Task Force Destiny to Kandahar Airfield to be the aviation asset in southern Afghanistan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Petraeus ("Eagle 6") led the Screaming Eagles to war during the 2003 invasion of Iraq (Operation Iraqi Freedom).
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] General Petraeus led the division into Iraq saying, "Guidons, Guidons.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 101st Airborne Division's next Rendezvous with Destiny is North to Baghdad.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The division was in V Corps, providing support to the 3rd Infantry Division by clearing Iraqi strongpoints which that division had bypassed.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] 3rd Battalion, 187th Infantry (3rd Brigade) was attached to 3rd Infantry Division and was the main effort in clearing Saddam International Airport.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The division then served as part of the occupation forces of Iraq, using the city of Mosul as their primary base of operations.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] 1st and 2d Battalion, 327th Infantry Regiment (1st Brigade) oversaw the remote airfield Qayarrah West 30 miles (48 km) south of Mosul.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 502d Infantry Regiment (2d Brigade) and 3d Battalion, 327th Infantry Regiment were responsible for Mosul itself while the 187th Infantry Regiment (3d Brigade) controlled Tal Afar just west of Mosul.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 101st Airborne also participated in the Battle of Karbala.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The city had been bypassed during the advance on Baghdad, leaving American units to clear it in two days of street fighting against Iraqi irregular forces.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 101st Airborne was supported by the 2nd Battalion, 70th Armor Regiment with Charlie Company, 1st Battalion, 41st Infantry Regiment, 1st Armored Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 3d Battalion, 502d Infantry Regiment, 101st Airborne Division was awarded a Valorous Unit Award for their combat performance.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] On the afternoon of 22 July 2003, troops of the 101st Airborne 3/327th Infantry HQ and C-Company, aided by U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Special Forces killed Qusay Hussein, his 14-year-old son Mustapha, and his older brother Uday, during a raid on a home in Mosul.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] After Task Force 121 members were wounded, the 3/327th Infantry surrounded and fired on the house with a TOW missile, Mark 19 Automatic Grenade Launcher, M2 50 Caliber Machine guns and small arms.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] After about four hours of battle (the whole operation lasted six hours), the soldiers entered the house and found four dead, including the two brothers and their bodyguard.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] There were reports that Qusay's 14-year-old son Mustapha was the fourth body found.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Frank Helmick, the assistant commander of 101st Airborne, commented that all occupants of the house died during the fierce gun battle before U.S. troops entered.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Once replaced by the first operational Stryker Brigade, the 101st was withdrawn in early 2004 for rest and refit.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] As part of the Army's modular transformation, the existing infantry brigades, artillery brigade, and aviation brigades were transformed.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The Army also activated the 4th Brigade Combat Team, which includes the 1st and 2nd Battalions, 506th Infantry Regiment and subordinate units.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Both battalions were part of the 101st in Vietnam but saw their colors inactivated during an Army-wide reflagging of combat battalions in the 1980s.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] As of December 2007, 143 members of the division have died while on service in Iraq.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The division's second deployment to Iraq began in the late summer of 2005.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The division headquarters replaced the 42d Infantry Division, which had been directing security operations as the headquarters for Task Force Liberty.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Renamed Task Force Band of Brothers, the 101st assumed responsibility on 1 November 2005 for four provinces in north central Iraq: Salah ad Din, As Sulymaniyah.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] During the second deployment, 2d and 4th Brigades of the 101st Airborne Division were assigned to conduct security operations under the command of Task Force Baghdad, led initially by 3d Infantry Division, which was replaced by 4th Infantry Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 1st Battalion of the 506th Infantry (4th Brigade) was separated from the division and served with the Marines in Ramadi, in the Al Anbar province.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] 3d Brigade was assigned to Salah ad Din and Bayji sectors and 1st Brigade was assigned to the overall Kirkuk province which included Hawijah.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Task Force Band of Brothers' primary mission during its second deployment to Iraq was the training of Iraqi security forces.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] When the 101st returned to Iraq, there were no Iraqi units capable of assuming the lead for operations against Iraqi and foreign terrorists.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] As the division concluded its tour, 33 battalions were in the lead for security in assigned areas, and two of four Iraq divisions in northern Iraq were commanding and controlling subordinate units.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Simultaneously with training Iraqi soldiers and their leaders, 101st soldiers conducted numerous security operations against terrorist cells operating in the division's assigned, six-province area of operations.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Operation Swarmer was the largest air assault operation conducted in Iraq since 22 April 2003.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] 1st Brigade conducted Operation Scorpion with Iraqi units near Kirkuk.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Developing other aspects of Iraqi society also figured in 101st operations in Iraq.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Division commander Major General Thomas Turner hosted the first governors' conference for the six provinces in the division's area of operations, as well as the neighboring province of Erbil.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The Division Headquarters, 101st Combat Aviation Brigade, 1st Brigade Combat Team, 2d Brigade Combat Team, 3rd Brigade Combat Team, and 4th Brigade Combat Team, and the 101st Sustainment Brigade deployed to Afghanistan in 2010.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] This is the first time since returning from Iraq in 2006 where all four infantry brigades (plus one CAB, SUSBDE) have served in the same combat theater.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] On 15 September 2010, the 101st Airborne began a major operation known as Operation Dragon Strike.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The aim of the operation was to reclaim the strategic southern province of Kandahar, which was the birthplace of the Taliban movement.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The area where the operation took place has been dubbed "The Heart of Darkness" by Coalition troops.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] By the end of December 2010, the operation's main objectives had been accomplished.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The majority of Taliban forces in Kandahar had withdrawn from the province, and much of their leadership was said to have been fractured.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] As of 5 June 2011, 131 soldiers had been killed during this deployment, the highest death toll to the 101st Airborne in any single deployment since the Vietnam War.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 2nd Battalion, 327th Infantry Regiment conducted a major combat operation in Barawala Kalay Valley, Kunar Province, Afghanistan in late March–April 2011.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] It is known as the Battle of Barawala Kalay Valley.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] It was an operation to close down the Taliban supply route through the Barawala Kalay Valley and to remove the forces of Taliban warlord Qari Ziaur Rahman from the Barwala Kalay Valley.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 2nd Battalion, 327th Infantry Regiment would suffer 6 killed and 7 wounded during combat operations.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] It would inflict over 100 casualties on the Taliban and successfully close down the Taliban supply route.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] ABC News correspondent Mike Boettcher was on scene and he called it the fiercest fighting he has ever seen in his 30 years of being in war zones.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Since the beginning of Operation Enduring Freedom 166 101st Airborne soldiers have died while serving in Iraq.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] In 2014, the 101st Airborne Division Headquarters deployed to west Africa to help contain the spread of Ebola, as part of Operation United Assistance.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Earlier in April 2014, 4th Brigade Combat Team had been inactivated as part of the Army's 2020 BCT restructuring program.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] In 2015, 5th Special Forces Group held five training sessions with the 1st Brigade Combat Team, 101st Airborne Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The classes covered communications and the operation of all-terrain vehicles.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] There was also a training session on the operation of TOW missiles.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Prior to these sessions training between U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Special Forces and U.S. conventional forces had been uncommon.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] It was announced 14 January 2016 that soldiers of the 101st Airborne would be assigned rotations in Iraq, to train members of the Iraqi ground forces in preparation for action against the Islamic State.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Defense Secretary Ash Carter told the 101st Airborne that "The Iraqi and Peshmerga forces you will train, advise and assist have proven their determination, their resiliency, and increasingly, their capability.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] But they need you to continue building on that success, preparing them for the fight today and the long hard fight for their future.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] In spring 2016, 2nd Brigade deployed to Iraq in support of Operation Inherent Resolve, a US-led coalition with the mission of defeating the Islamic State.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The Strike Brigade conducted precision surface-to-surface fires and supported a multitude of intelligence and logistical operations for coalition and Iraqi forces.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] They also provided base security throughout more than 12 areas of operations.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The Brigade also aided in the clearance of ISIS from Fallujah, the near elimination of suicide attacks in Baghdad, and the introduction of improved tactics that liberated more than 100 towns and villages.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 2nd Brigade also played a significant role in the liberation of Mosul.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] 200 soldiers from 1st Battalion, 320th Field Artillery Regiment, 2nd Brigades field artillery battalion, replaced a unit of the 26th MEU at Firebase Bell; they used M777 155mm howitzers to provide support to Iraqi forces attacking IS-occupied villages between Makhmour and Mosul.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] On 26 June 2016, it was announced that Iraq had successfully taken back full control of Fallujah from the Islamic State of Iraq (ISIS).
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Iraqi ground troops have been under the direction of the 101st Airborne since early 2016.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] On 26 August 2016, an article from the website War is Boring shows a photo of a 101st Airborne Division M777 howitzer crew conducting fire missions during an operation to support Iraqi forces at Kara Soar Base in Iraq on 7 August 2016.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The article also confirms that American artillery has been supporting Iraqi forces during its campaign against ISIS.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] On 21 September 2016, an article from *The Leaf-Chronicle* reported that Battery C, 1st Battalion, 320th Field Artillery Regiment, 2nd Brigade Combat Team, 101st Airborne Division had been successfully conducting artillery raids against the Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Battery C is said to have executed hundreds of missions and fired thousands of rounds in support of ISF operations since arriving in theatre in late May.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] On 17 October 2016, an article from *The Leaf-Chronicle* stated that the 101st Airborne was leading a coalition of 19 nations to support the liberation of Mosul from ISIL.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Under the direction of the 101st Iraqi forces have taken back a significant amount of geography from the control of ISIS.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] This included the liberation of Hit, Fallujah, and Qayyarah.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] On 3 November 2016, it was reported that U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Army combat engineers were seen just west of the Great Zab River about halfway between the Kurdish city of Irbil and Mosul.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] They were searching for improvised bombs.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] They were wearing 101st Airborne Division patches.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The soldiers said they were not allowed to talk to the media.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] On 17 November 2016, sources reported that the 101st Airborne Division was headed home after a nine-month deployment to Iraq.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Over the course of nine months, soldiers from the 101st Airborne helped train the Iraqi government's security forces.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] They taught marksmanship, basic battlefield medical care and ways to detect and disarm improvised explosive devices.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The division helped authorize 6,900 strikes, meant to destroy ISIS hideouts and staging areas.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 101st Airborne played a significant role in the liberation of several Iraqi cities during this deployment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] 1st Brigade "Bastogne" deployed troops to Iraq and Syria in January 2019, returning the following September.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] It was reported that many Combat Action Badges had been award, primarily to artillery batteries conducting fire missions against Islamic State fighters, with some Combat Infantryman Badges issued to troops in northern Syria.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Senior leadership referred to the 3rd Brigade Combat Team as being exceptional.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Scott Brower stated that the Rakkasans are trained, well-led, and prepared to accomplish any mission given to them.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] During this deployment three Soldiers from 1/187, 3rd Brigade Combat Team died as a result of an insider attack by an Afghan Soldier.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] In mid-April 2017, it was reported that 40 soldiers from the 101st Airborne Division were deployed to Somalia on 2 April 2017 to improve the capabilities of the Somali Army in combating Islamist militants.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] AFRICOM stated that the troops will focus on bolstering the Somali army's logistics capabilities; an AFRICOM spokesman said that "This mission is not associated with teaching counterextremism tactics" and that the Somali government requested the training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] In June 2022, Headquarters, 101st Airborne Division (Air Assault) and the 2nd Brigade Combat Team rotated in to the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Army V Corps' mission to reinforce NATO's eastern flank and engage in multinational exercises with partners across the European continent in order to reassure allies and deter further Russian aggression during its invasion of Ukraine.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 101st soldiers deploying to Mihail Kogălniceanu in June did not represent additional U.S. forces in Europe, but are taking the place of soldiers assigned to 82nd Airborne Division Headquarters and the 3rd Infantry Brigade Combat Team of the 82nd Airborne Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] In all, approximately 4700 soldiers from the 101st Airborne Division are scheduled to deploy to locations across Europe.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] On 30 July 2022, the Headquarters, 101st Airborne Division and 2nd Brigade Combat Team uncased their colors and conducted an air assault demonstration at the 57th Air Base "Mihail Kogălniceanu" together with the 9th Mechanized Brigade of the Romanian Armed Forces.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] McGee and the Prime Minister of Romania, Nicolae Ciucă.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 2nd Brigade Combat Team was replaced by the 1st Brigade Combat Team on 31 March 2023.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] During its 9 months of deployment, the 2nd Brigade conducted training exercises with multiple NATO partners and allies across the continent.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] On 5 April, the mission authority was transferred from the 101st Division to the 10th Mountain Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The battle flag of the 101st was also decorated with the National Order of Faithful Service during the ceremony.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] On 24 November, the 3rd Brigade Combat Team "Rakkasan" replaced the 1st Brigade Combat Team following a transfer of authority ceremony.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] In response to the damage inflicted by Hurricane Helene, soldiers of the 2nd Mobile Brigade Combat Team "Strike" and 101st Combat Aviation Brigade began deploying on 5 October 2024, to western North Carolina.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The mission was Defense Support of Civil Authorities under the control of United States Army North.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Soldiers from the 101st provided support to civil authorities in search and rescue, medical aid, route assessment and clearance, traffic control, warehouse management, supply distribution, debris removal, general transportation and equipment maintenance tasks.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] Strike Soldiers used newly issued Infantry Squad Vehicles and 101 CAB helicopters to access areas with damaged road infrastructure to carry out relief efforts.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] As part of continued reorganization, the 2nd Squadron, 17th Cavalry Regiment, part of the Combat Aviation Brigade, cased it colors in a ceremony held on 15 May 2026 at Fort Campbell.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-airborne-division-p03] The 101st Airborne Division consists of a division headquarters and headquarters battalion, three mobile brigades, division artillery, a combat aviation brigade, a sustainment brigade.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The **101st Cavalry Regiment** is a unit of the New York National Guard that has seen service in the American Civil War, the Spanish–American War, the Mexican Border Conflict, World War I, World War II, and the War in Afghanistan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] It also carries the lineage of the former 1st Battalion, 127th Armored Regiment (originally founded in 1838), and 1st Battalion, 210th Armor (originally founded in 1860).
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] Currently, the regiment consists of one squadron, the 2nd Squadron, 101st Cavalry.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The 101st Cavalry Regiment was constituted in the National Guard on 30 December 1920, assigned to the 21st Cavalry Division, and allotted to the state of New York.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] It was organized on 1 June 1921 by redesignation of the 1st New York Cavalry Regiment as the 101st Cavalry.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The regimental headquarters was organized on 11 July 1921 and federally recognized at Brooklyn.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] Subordinate squadron headquarters were organized and federally recognized as follows: 1st Squadron organized on 6 June 1921 at Brooklyn; 2nd Squadron organized on 1 June 1921 at Buffalo.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The entire 2nd Squadron was reassigned on 15 February 1928 as part of the new 121st Cavalry Regiment, and a new 2nd Squadron organized from the 51st Machine Gun Squadron at Manhattan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] Reorganized on 25 May 1929 as a three-squadron regiment, with the new 3rd Squadron organized at Manhattan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The 2nd Squadron participated in a review on 7 June 1930 for Governor Franklin D.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] Roosevelt at Van Cortlandt Park in the Bronx.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The regiment provided escort to Prince and Princess Takamatsu of Japan on 11 April 1931 during their visit to New York City.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The regiment conducted summer training at Fort Ethan Allen, Vermont, from 1921–25 (less 1923), Camp Dix, New Jersey, in 1923, and Pine Camp, New York, from 1926–39, and conducted additional week-long winter training directed by the War Department at Plattsburg Barracks, New York, in December 1939.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The regiment was reorganized and redesignated as the 101st Cavalry Regiment (Horse and Mechanized) on 1 October 1940 and relieved from the 21st Cavalry Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] It was assigned to the VI Corps on 30 December 1940.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] It was inducted into active federal service at home stations on 27 January 1941 and transferred to Fort Devens, Massachusetts, arriving there on 4 February 1941.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] With this organization, the group saw combat in northwest Europe during World War II with the XV and the XXI Corps of the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] Late in the war it was attached to the 12th Armored Division of XXI Corps.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] Among other exploits, troops of the 101st Cavalry captured German field marshal Albert Kesselring as well as the Japanese ambassador to Germany in May 1945.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] Following the war, the 101st Group was inactivated on 25 October 1945 at Camp Myles Standish, Massachusetts.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The regiment was reformed as the *101st Armored Cavalry Regiment* on 1 January 1950 with headquarters again at Brooklyn.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] On 16 March 1959, the unit was retitled the *101st Armored Regiment*, which endured until 15 April 1963 when the unit was renamed the *101st Cavalry*, reduced in strength to one squadron, and subordinated to the 42nd Infantry Division.Pope, pp.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] In 1993, the 101st was consolidated with the 1st Battalion, 210th Armor, taking the 210th's lineage and battle honors but keeping its designation as the 101st Cavalry.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The 1st squadron of the 101st Cavalry was disbanded in August 2006.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The 2nd Squadron remains, and is headquartered in Niagara Falls, New York.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] 2nd Squadron is the reconnaissance squadron of the 27th IBCT, and they consist of A Troop (Mounted) stationed in Geneva, New York, B Troop (Mounted), and C Troop (Dismounted).
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The 2nd Squadron also carries the lineage of the 1st Battalion, 127th Armor Regiment, which converted into the 2nd Squadron, 101st Cavalry when the New York National Guard reorganized in 2005–2006.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The squadron deployed to Afghanistan in 2008 and again in 2012.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] The Squadron, with additional support from the 27th IBCT, deployed to Ukraine in 2017 in order to support the training of Ukrainian soldiers.
[src:10th-mountain-division/101st-cavalry-regiment] Elements of the Squadron deployed to Germany and Horn of Africa in 2022.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The **102nd Infantry Division** ("**Ozark**") was a unit of the United States Army in World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The unit is currently active as the **102nd Training Division (Maneuver Support)**.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] On 23 July 1918, the War Department directed the organization of the 102nd Division at Camp Dix, New Jersey.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] It was intended that the 203rd Infantry Brigade would be organized in France from the 60th and 61st Pioneer Infantry Regiments.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The 29th Trench Mortar Battery was formed at Camp Kearny, California, in August 1918.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] No division staff members were ever appointed, but cadre personnel for the division were designated and reported to Camp Dix before orders to demobilize were given on 30 November 1918 after the armistice with Germany.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The division was constituted in the Organized Reserve on 24 June 1921, allotted to the Seventh Corps Area, and assigned to the XVII Corps, with Arkansas and Missouri as its home area.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The headquarters was organized on 2 September 1921 at 3rd and Olive Streets in St.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] Louis, and relocated in 1923 to the Old Customhouse.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The headquarters remained there until activated for World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The designated mobilization and training station for the division was Fort Riley, Kansas.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The headquarters and staff usually trained at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The subordinate infantry regiments of the division held their summer training primarily with the 17th Infantry Regiment at Fort Leavenworth.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] Other units, such as the special troops, artillery, engineers, aviation, medical, and quartermaster, trained at various posts in the Sixth and Seventh Corps Areas, often with the active units of the 7th Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] In addition to the unit training camps, the infantry regiments of the division rotated responsibility to conduct the Citizens Military Training Camps held at Fort Leavenworth each year.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] On a number of occasions, the division participated in Seventh Corps Area and Fourth Army command post exercises in conjunction with other Regular Army, National Guard, and Organized Reserve units.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] Unlike the Regular and Guard units in the Seventh Corps Area, the 102nd Division did not participate in the various Seventh Corps Area maneuvers and the Fourth Army maneuvers of 1937, 1940, and 1941 as an organized unit due to lack of enlisted personnel and equipment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] Truman, a lieutenant colonel in the Officers' Reserve Corps, commanded the division's 1st Battalion, 379th Field Artillery Regiment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] After promotion to colonel, Truman advanced to command of the 379th Field Artillery Regiment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The 408th Infantry Regiment was inactivated by relief of remaining Reserve personnel on 6 January 1942, and disbanded on 11 November 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The 102nd Infantry Division, under the command of Major General Frank A.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] Keating, arrived on the Western Front in the European Theater of Operations (ETO) at Cherbourg, France, 23 September 1944, and, after a short period of training near Valognes, moved to the German-Netherlands border.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] On 26 October, elements attached to other divisions entered combat and on 3 November the division assumed responsibility for the sector from the Wurm to Waurichen.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] A realignment of sectors and the return of elements placed the 102nd in full control of its units for the first time, 24 November 1944, as it prepared for an attack to the Roer.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The attack jumped off, 29 November, and carried the division to the river through Welz, Flossdorf, and Linnich.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] After a period of aggressive patrolling along the Roer, 4–19 December, the division took over the XIII Corps sector from the Wurm River, north of the village of Wurm, to Barmen on the south, and trained for river crossing.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] On 23 February 1945, the 102d attacked across the Roer (Operation Grenade), advanced toward Lövenich and Erkelenz, bypassed Mönchengladbach, took Krefeld, 3 March, and reached the Rhine.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] During March the division was on the defensive along the Rhine, its sector extending from Homburg south to Düsseldorf.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] Crossing the river on 9 April on pontoon bridge, the division attacked in the Wesergebirge, meeting stiff opposition.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] After 3 days and nights of terrific enemy resistance Wilsede and Hessisch-Oldendorf fell, 12 April 1945, and the 102d pushed on to the Elbe, meeting little resistance.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] Breitenfeld fell, 15 April, and the division outposted the Elbe River, 48 miles from Berlin, its advance halted on orders.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] Storkau experienced fighting on the 16th, EHRA on the 21st along with Fallersleben.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] On 3 May 1945 the 102nd shook hands with the Russian 156th Division just outside Berlin.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] On 15 April the division discovered a war crime in Gardelegen: the Isenschnibbe Barn Atrocity.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] About 1,200 prisoners from the Mittelbau-Dora and Hannover-Stöcken concentration camps were forced from a train into an empty barn measuring approximately a hundred by fifty feet on the outskirts of the town.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The barn was then set afire, killing those inside.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] However, two men survived, buried under a shield of dead bodies, protecting them from the gunfire and flames.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] When the first soldiers arrived at the barn, the two came crawling out from under the dead and burning bodies.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] Major General Keating ordered that the nearby civilian population be forced to view the site and to disinter and rebury the victims in a new cemetery.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] After digging the graves and burying the bodies, they erected a Christian Cross or a Jewish Star of David over each grave and enclosed the site with a white fence.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] Today both the former crime scene and the Cemetery of Honour are parts of the Isenschnibbe Barn Memorial Gardelegen.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The division patrolled and maintained defensive positions until the end of hostilities in Europe, then moved to Gotha for occupation duty.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] On 1 June 1959, the division was reorganized as a Pentomic Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The division's three infantry regiments were inactivated and their elements reorganized into five infantry battle groups.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] On 1 April 1963, the division was reorganized as a Reorganization Objective Army Division (ROAD).
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The division and subordinate elements were inactivated on 31 December 1965.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The lineage of the 102d Division is perpetuated by the 102d Training Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The division was reactivated on September 16, 2008 as the 102nd Training Division; with headquarters concurrently activated at Fort Snelling, Minnesota.
[src:10th-mountain-division/102nd-infantry-division-united-states] The 102nd Training Division (Maneuver Support) is a subordinate unit of the 80th Training Command (The Army School System — TASS).
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The **103rd Infantry Division** ("**Cactus Division**") was a unit of the United States Army that served in the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Seventh Army of the 6th Army Group during World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] It was variously assigned to the VI Corps, XV Corps, and XXI Corps.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] By war's end it was part of VI Corps' dash across Bavaria into the Alps, reaching Innsbruck, Austria, taking the Brenner Pass, and earning the honor of linking up with the United States Fifth Army coming north from Vipiteno, Italy, joining the Italian and Western European fronts on 4 May 1945.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The 103rd Division was constituted in the Organized Reserve on 24 June 1921, allotted to the Eighth Corps Area, and assigned to the XVIII Corps.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The division was further allotted to the states of Arizona, Colorado, and New Mexico as its home area.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The division headquarters was organized on 31 August 1921, at the State Capitol in Denver.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The headquarters was moved on 29 March 1922 to the Kittredge Building at 16th Street and Glenarm Place in Denver and remained there until activated for World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] To encourage esprit de corps, in 1922 the division’s officers adopted the nickname “Rocky Mountain Division” after the majestic mountain range that defined much of the division’s home area.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] However, this nickname soon gave way to the moniker “Cactus Division” after the unit’s shoulder patch.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Inactive training period activities of the division were generally conducted at the local level near concentrations of division personnel.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] One event that turned out large numbers of the Denver members of the division was the Memorial Day parade held in that city each year.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The subordinate infantry regiments of the division held their summer training with the 25th Infantry Regiment at Fort Huachuca and Camp Stephen D.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Little, Arizona, and with the 1st Battalion, 38th Infantry Regiment. at Fort Logan, Colorado.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Other units, such as the special troops, artillery, engineers, aviation, medical, and quartermaster, trained at various posts in the Eighth Corps Area.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] For example, the division’s artillery regiments trained at Fort Bliss, Texas, with the 82nd Field Artillery, or at Fort Francis E.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] On a number of occasions, the division participated in Eighth Corps Area and Third Army command post exercises (CPXs) in conjunction with other Regular Army, National Guard, and Organized Reserve units.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Unlike the Regular and Guard units in the Eighth Corps Area, however, the 103rd Division did not participate in the various Eighth Corps Area Maneuvers and the Third Army maneuvers of 1938, 1940, and 1941 as an organized unit due to lack of enlisted personnel and equipment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] However, for each maneuver, the division maximized the number of participants.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] For example, for the 1938 maneuvers at Fort Francis E.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Warren, Fort Bliss, and Fort Huachuca, the 103rd Division provided 228 officers to Regular Army units and 53 to units of the National Guard's 45th Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Similar numbers participated in the two succeeding Army maneuvers.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The 103rd Infantry Division was ordered into active military service on 15 November 1942 at Camp Claiborne, Louisiana.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] After nearly two years of training, the 103rd departed the United States for Europe on 5 October 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The division arrived at Marseille, France, 20 October 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] It relieved the 3d Division at Chevry on 8 November, arrived at Docelles (Vosges) on 9 November, and attacked west of St.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Dié, 16 November, in its drive through the Vosges.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Meeting heavy resistance all the way, it crossed the Meurthe River, took St.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Dié on 23 November and captured Diefenbach on 29 November and Selestat on 4 December.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The division crossed the Zintzel river at Griesbach, 10 December 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Pushing through Climbach, the 103rd crossed the Lauter River into Germany, 15 December, and assaulted the outer defenses of the Siegfried Line.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] On 22 December, the division moved west to the Sarreguemines area where an active defense was maintained.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The enemy offensive did not develop in its sector and the 103rd moved to Reichshofen, 14 January 1945, to take up positions along the Sauer River.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] On 15 January, General Anthony "Nuts" McAuliffe was redeployed from the Battle of the Bulge and given command, which he retained until July 1945.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Defensive patrols were active and a limited attack on Soufflenheim on 19 January was repulsed by the enemy.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] On 20 January, the division withdrew to the Moder and repulsed German advances near Muehlhausen, 23–25 January.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The 103rd's offensive began on 15 March 1945.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Crossing the Moder and Zintzel rivers and taking Muehlhausen against sharp opposition, the division moved over the Lauter river and penetrated the defenses of the Siegfried Line.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] As German resistance disintegrated, the 103rd reached the Upper Rhine Valley, 23 March, and engaged in mopping up operations in the plain west of the River Rhine.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] In April 1945, it received occupational duties until 20 April when it resumed the offensive, pursuing a fleeing enemy through Stuttgart and taking Münsingen on 24 April.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] On 27 April, elements of the division entered Landsberg, where Kaufering concentration camp, a subcamp of Dachau, was liberated.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The men of the division crossed the Danube River near Ulm on 26 April.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] On 3 May 1945, members of its 409th Infantry Regiment captured Innsbruck, Austria with little to no fighting.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The 411th Infantry Regiment continued on to take the Brenner Pass and earn the honor of linking up with the 88th Infantry Division of the Fifth Army, which had been fighting its way north up the Italian peninsula.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Troops met at Vipiteno, Italy, near the Austrian border, on 4 May 1945, joining the Italian and Western European fronts.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] After Victory in Europe Day, the division received occupational duties until it left for home and inactivation.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] It returned to the continental U.S. on 10 September 1945, and was inactivated on 22 September 1945 at Camp Kilmer, New Jersey.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The 103rd was activated as an Organized Reserve Corps division on 7 May 1947 in Des Moines, Iowa.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] Its combat elements were reorganized and redesignated as the 205th Infantry Brigade and the 103rd Operational Headquarters in February 1963.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The 103rd Operational Headquarters was redesignated as the 103rd Command Headquarters (Divisional) in June 1963.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] In December 1965, the unit was reorganized as the 103rd Support Brigade.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] In September 1977, the unit was redesignated and reorganized as the 103rd Corps Support Command (COSCOM), the first Corps Support Command in the United States Army Reserve.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] On 15 September 1993, the 103rd COSCOM inactivated, followed by the creation of two new reserve units: 19th Theater Army Area Command (CONUS) and 3d COSCOM (CONUS).
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] On 14 February 2006, the 103rd was redesignated as Headquarters and Headquarters Company, 103rd Sustainment Command.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The 103rd Expeditionary Sustainment Command was activated as a reserve command, effective 16 September 2006.
[src:10th-mountain-division/103rd-infantry-division-united-states] The division shoulder patch is worn by the United States Army Reserve 103rd Sustainment Command (Expeditionary).
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The **104th Infantry Division** was an infantry division of the United States Army.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Today it exists as the **104th Training Division (Leader Training)**, a component of the United States Army Reserve headquartered at Joint Base Lewis–McChord, Washington.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] It is one of three training divisions subordinate to the 108th Training Command.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division's 1st Brigade provides Cadet Summer Training (CST) to Reserve Officers' Training Corps units and support to Senior Reserve Officers' Training Corps personnel (SROTC).
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division's 2nd Brigade provides Basic Combat Training (BCT) to drill sergeants and also provides support to the United States Military Academy.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division is slated to be deactivated by October 2026.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] This was the only combat duty that the 104th Infantry Division has served during its history.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] At the end of the fighting on 7 May 1945 (V-E Day), this division was in central Germany opposite the troops of its allies from the Soviet Army.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] After World War II, this division was reorganized primarily as a training division for Reserve forces.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] After several decades, the division then expanded its role to conducting entry-level training for soldiers of all branches of the Army in the northwestern United States.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Its role and size have expanded over that time due to the consolidation of other training commands, and the division subsequently took charge of a number of brigades specializing in various entry-level training for soldiers of all types.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 104th Division was constituted in the Organized Reserve on 24 June 1921, allotted to the Ninth Corps Area, and assigned to the XIX Corps.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division was allocated to the states of Utah, Idaho, Montana, and Wyoming as its home area, although the 2nd Battalion, 413th Infantry was organized at Reno, Nevada.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division headquarters was organized on 7 October 1921 at Fort Douglas, Utah, and relocated in May 1923 to Room 312 in the Commercial Building in Salt Lake City.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The headquarters was moved on 30 September 1926 to the Vermont Building where it remained until activated for World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] To maintain communications with the officers of the division, the division staff published a newsletter titled “Frontier Division,” which was reflective of the unit's geographical area.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The newsletter informed the division's members what the division's summer training quotas were, where the camps were to be held, and which units would be assigned to help conduct the Citizens Military Training Camps (CMTC).
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] For the few summers when the division headquarters was called to duty for training as a unit, the 104th Division usually trained with the staff of the 3rd Division's 6th Infantry Brigade at Fort Douglas.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The subordinate infantry regiments of the division held their summer training primarily with the units of the 3rd Division at Fort Douglas and Fort Missoula, Montana, and some years with the 2nd Division's 4th Infantry Brigade at the Pole Mountain Military Reservation, Wyoming.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Other units, however, such as the special troops, artillery, engineers, aviation, medical, and quartermaster, trained at various posts in the Ninth Corps Area with Regular Army units of the same branch.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] For example, the 329th Engineer Regiment usually trained with elements of the 3rd Division's 6th Engineer Regiment at Camp Lewis, Washington, and the 329th Medical Regiment trained at the post hospital at Fort Francis E.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] In addition to the unit training camps, the infantry regiments of the division rotated responsibility to conduct the CMTC held at Camp Lewis each year.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] On a number of occasions, the division participated in Ninth Corps Area and Fourth Army command post exercises in conjunction with other Regular Army, National Guard, and Organized Reserve units.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Unlike the Regular and Guard units in the Ninth Corps Area, however, the 104th Division did not participate in the various Ninth Corps Area maneuvers and the major Fourth Army maneuvers of 1936 and 1940 as an organized unit due to lack of enlisted personnel and equipment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Instead, the officers and a few enlisted reservists were assigned to the Regular and Guard units to fill vacant slots and bring the units up to full peace strength for the exercises.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 104th Infantry Division was ordered into active military service on 15 September 1942 under the command of Major General Gilbert R.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Cook, and was reorganized as the 104th Infantry Division at Camp Adair, Oregon.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division earned its nickname "Timberwolf Division" from its time in the northwest.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Army division to be trained to fight in nighttime conditions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] After training at Camp Adair, the division participated in the Oregon Maneuver combat exercise in the fall of 1943.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] On 15 October 1943, Major General Terry de la Mesa Allen Sr. took command of the division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] He had previously commanded the 1st Infantry Division, "The Big Red One", in North Africa and Sicily and would command the 104th during most of its time in combat.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] On 7 December 1943, the division moved to, and began 13 weeks of desert training at Camp Hyder, Arizona.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division concluded training on 9 February 1944, and next moved to Camp Granite, California.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] One last move in March to Camp Carson, Colorado, aboard 24 trains was followed with a cross-county move to Camp Kilmer, New Jersey, arriving on 20 August 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 104th Infantry Division sailed for the Western Front on 27 August 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] It landed in France on 7 September 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division was assigned to III Corps of the Ninth United States Army, part of the Twelfth United States Army Group.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division then organized and assembled at Manche, France before heading into combat.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Joining the Battle of the Scheldt, the division moved into defensive positions in the vicinity of Wuustwezel, Belgium on 23 October 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The Timberwolves were then assigned to Field Marshal Sir Bernard Montgomery's Anglo-Canadian 21st Army Group under the British I Corps, within the First Canadian Army, along with the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] 7th Armored Division, in order to clear out the Scheldt Estuary and open the port of Antwerp.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] 7th Armored Division was assigned static duty holding the right flank of the gains made during the failed Market Garden operation, the 104th Infantry Division was to participate in the First Canadian Army's taking of the Scheldt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The Americans were given responsibility for taking 22 miles of wet, low country from the Belgian border to the Meuse (*Maas*).
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The width of their front was approximately 8,000 yards.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] General Allen planned to employ all three of his regiments at the same time, shoulder to shoulder.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 104th began combat operations on 25 and 26 October and began to attack the Germans, who offered varying levels of resistance.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Along the division's front, the Germans were spread thinly and did not have continuous lines of defense.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] However, they did possess deadly strong points and endeavored to make the Timberwolves' progress as time-consuming and costly as possible, making heavy use of mines, booby traps, and roadblocks.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Despite this, the advance was steady, though paid for in the lives of the 104th Division soldiers.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Conditions were rainy, chilly, wet, and muddy.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Moisture seemed to grip everything and everyone.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Sleet beat down on the troops, who went for days soaked to the skin and slimy with mud.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] On 30 October, after five days of continuous operations the division had pushed about 15 miles to within sight of the Mark River and had liberated Zundert, gained control of the Breda-Roosendaal Road, and overrun the Vaart Canal defenses.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Leur and Etten fell as the division advanced to the Mark River, arriving there by 31 October.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] A coordinated attack over the Mark River at Standdaarbuiten on 2 November established a bridgehead and the rest of the division crossed the river.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] With the Allies firmly on the north side of the Mark River, German resistance collapsed.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] For the next two days, the Timberwolves pursued enemy remnants north to the Meuse.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Zevenbergen was captured and the Meuse was reached on 5 November.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] That same day, General Allen received orders from the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] First Army, releasing it from Canadian control.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] While the bulk of the division moved near Aachen, Germany, elements remained to secure Moerdijk until 7 November, when they were relieved.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] During this time, the division was reassigned to VII Corps of the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] 1st Army, also part of the Twelfth Army Group.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] By 7 November, the fighting in the Netherlands cost the Timberwolves 1,426 casualties, including 313 killed and 103 missing.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The Royal Navy took three weeks to sweep the estuary waters clear of mines, and in early December 1944, the port of Antwerp was open to Allied shipping.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] While under American command on 16 November 1944, the division went on another offensive in support of Operation Queen, taking Stolberg and pushing on against heavy resistance.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Eschweiler fell on 21 November and the enemy was cleared from the area west of the Inde River, including Inden by 2 December 1944.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Lucherberg was held against enemy counterattacks on 3 December, and all strongholds west of the Roer River were captured by the 23rd.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] It took temporary command of the 60th Infantry Regiment of the 9th Infantry Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] During the Battle of the Bulge, the 104th actively defended its sector near Duren and Merken (in German only) from 15 December 1944 to 22 February 1945.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] During that time, it was reassigned to XIX Corps of the Ninth United States Army.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] It then moved across the Roer taking Huchem-Stammeln, Birkesdorf, and North Duren.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] On 5 March, after heavy fighting, it entered Köln.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] After defending the west bank of the Rhine River, the division crossed the river at Honnef on 22 March 1945, and attacked to the east of the Remagen bridgehead.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] During this time, some of the division's assets fell under command of the 1st Infantry Division and the 3rd Armored Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] After a period of mopping up and consolidation, it participated in the trap of enemy troops in the Ruhr pocket.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 104th repulsed heavy attacks near Medebach and captured Paderborn on 1 April 1945.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] After regrouping, it advanced to the east and crossed the Weser River on 8 April, blocking enemy exits from the Harz Mountains.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] On 11 April 1945 the Division was involved in the liberation of a large German concentration camp at Nordhausen.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division then crossed the Saale River and took Halle in a bitter five-day struggle from 15 to 19 April.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The sector to the Mulde River was cleared by 21 April, and after vigorous patrolling, contacted the Red Army at Pretzsch on 26 April.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division took temporary command of assets from the 69th Infantry Division in early May.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division returned to the United States on 3 July 1945, where it began making preparations for deployment to the Pacific Theater.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] After Japan surrendered, the division began the process of demobilization.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division was inactivated at Camp San Luis Obispo, California on 20 December 1945.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] During World War II, soldiers of the division were awarded two Medals of Honor, 14 Distinguished Service Crosses, one Distinguished Service Medal, 642 Silver Star Medals, six Legion of Merit medals, 20 Soldier's Medals, 2,797 Bronze Star Medals, and 40 Air Medals.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division received 9 Distinguished Unit Citations and three campaign streamers during 200 days of combat.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division was reactivated on 1 December 1946 in the organized reserves in Portland, Oregon.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] It began taking on the responsibility of holding training programs for new soldiers of the US Army Reserve.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] In July 1948, the division held its first session of summer training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] By the end of the training, it had turned out 300 new reservists.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] By 1952, the division was turning out 1,500 new reservists per training camp.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The division was reorganized specifically as a training division in 1959.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] In 1961, the division was relocated to Vancouver Barracks, Washington.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] As part of an army-wide initiative known as the Reorganization Objective Army Division plan, the division's regiments were disbanded and replaced with larger and more versatile brigades.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 1st Brigade, 104th Division, activated at Vancouver Barracks, and the 2nd Brigade, 104th Division activated at Pasco, Washington.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Meanwhile, the 3rd Brigade, 104th Division, as well as the 4th Brigade, 104th Division both activated at Fort Lawton, Washington.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Each of these brigades carried the history of other historic units which fought under the 104th Infantry Division in World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 104th Division was then assigned the mission of conducting One Station Unit Training, Basic Combat Training, Advanced Individual Training, and Combat Support training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] 1st Brigade took on basic combat training, while 3rd Brigade undertook combat support training, 4th Brigade conducted combat service support training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] In 1996, three more brigades were added to the division's structure.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 5th Brigade, 104th Division was activated at Salt Lake City, Utah.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 6th Brigade, 104th Division was activated at Aurora, Colorado.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 7th Brigade, 104th Division activated at Vancouver, Washington.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 5th Brigade conducted health services training, 6th Brigade took charge of professional development training and 7th Brigade provided training support to the other brigades.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] These units were redesignated from other training commands and put under the command of the division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] In 2005, the Base Realignment and Closure suggestions included the closure of the Vancouver Barracks, and the 104th Division was subsequently relocated to Fort Lewis, Washington.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] In 2005, the current Distinctive Unit Insignia was designed under the direction of Major General Terrill K.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 104th received its new distinctive unit insignia in 2006.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] In October 2007, the division was renamed the 104th Training Division (Leader Training).
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] This change reflected a change in the division's mission, specifically training officer and non-commissioned officer candidates in their assigned fields.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] The 104th Training Division is a subordinate unit of the 108th Training Command, which is tasked with providing Initial Entry Training (IET) to new recruits.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Besides providing training at their main training locations the division's battalions also operate numerous training detachments.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Several men who served with the 104th Infantry Division later went on to achieve notability for various reasons.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Among these are Rabbi Gunther Plaut, paleontologist Charles Repenning, Governor of Iowa Leo Hoegh, New York City Mayor Ed Koch, New York Governor Hugh L.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Snitzer was a member of the 104th and died in combat in 1945.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] NFL player Bob Shaw also served with the 104th and was awarded the Bronze Star during World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Screenwriter Paddy Chayefsky also served with the 104th during WW II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Bernard Moore was a member of the 104th Timberwolves and went on to be the manager at the Waldorf Astoria Towers in New York, later promoted to the Washington Hilton in Washington, DC.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Roberts, Purple Heart Medal recipient having stepped on a land mine on the French German border while going to get medic help for his sergeant for 30 plus years was the president of Robert Half Personnel Accountemps agencies with many US and Canadian locations.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] In addition, two soldiers from this division were awarded the Medal of Honor for their service in combat.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] James Jr., for scouting German positions while being pinned down by machine gun fire, and Cecil H.
[src:10th-mountain-division/104th-infantry-division-united-states] Bolton, who led a company of men on the attack despite wounds from a mortar shell.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The **10th Mountain Division (Light Infantry)** is a light infantry division in the United States Army based at Fort Drum, New York.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Formerly designated as a mountain warfare unit, the division was the only one of its size in the U.S. military to receive specialized training for fighting in mountainous conditions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Originally activated as the **10th Light Division (Alpine)** in 1943, the division was redesignated the 10th Mountain Division in 1944 and fought in the mountains of Italy in some of the roughest terrain in World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 5 May 1945, the division reached Nauders, Austria, just beyond the Reschen Pass, where it made contact with German s being pushed south by the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] A status quo was maintained until the enemy headquarters involved had completed their surrender to the Seventh.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 6 May, 10th Mountain troops met the 44th Infantry Division of Seventh Army.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Following the war, the division was deactivated, only to be reactivated and redesignated as the **10th Infantry Division** in 1948.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division first acted as a training division and, in 1954, was converted to a full combat division and, in 1955, was sent to Germany before being deactivated again in 1958.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Reactivated again in 1985, the division was designated the 10th Mountain Division (Light Infantry) to historically tie it to the World War II division and to also better describe its modern disposition.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Since its reactivation, the division or elements of the division have deployed numerous times.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Since 2001, the 10th Mountain Division has been the most deployed unit in the entire US military.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Its combat brigades have seen over 30 deployments, to both Iraq and Afghanistan, in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom and Operation Enduring Freedom, as well as Syria and parts of Africa in support of Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In November 1939, two months after World War II broke out in Europe, during the Soviet Union's invasion of Finland, Red Army efforts were frustrated following the destruction of two armored divisions by Finnish soldiers on skis.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The conflict caught attention as the outnumbered and outgunned Finnish soldiers were able to use the difficult local terrain to their advantage, severely hampering the Soviet attacks and embarrassing their military.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Upon seeing the effectiveness of these troops, Charles Minot "Minnie" Dole, the president of the National Ski Patrol, began to lobby the War Department of the need for a similar unit of troops in the United States Army, trained for fighting in winter and mountain warfare.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In September 1940, Dole was able to present his case to General George C.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Marshall, the Army Chief of Staff, who agreed with Dole's assessment, deciding to create a "Mountain" unit for fighting in harsh terrain.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army authorized the formation of the platoon-sized Army Ski Patrol in November 1940.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The first Patrol was formed at Camp Murray as part of the 41st Infantry Division under Lt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Phelps (later to become commanding General of the 41st).
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The army, prompted by fears that its standing would not perform well in the event of a winter attack on the Northeastern coast, as well as knowledge that the German Army already had three mountain warfare divisions known as Gebirgsjäger, approved the concept for a division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] This required an overhaul of U.S. military doctrine, as the concept of winter warfare had not been tested in the army since 1914.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] At first, planners envisioned ten mountain divisions, but personnel shortages revised the goal to three.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Eventually, the 10th Mountain Division would be the only one brought to active duty.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Italian military had lost a disastrous 25,000 men in the campaign because of their lack of preparedness to fight in the mountains.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 22 October 1941, General Marshall decided to form the first battalion of mountain warfare troops for a new mountain division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Ski Patrol would assist in its training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] It was the first mountain warfare unit in U.S. military history.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The National Ski Patrol took on the unique role of recruiting for the 87th Infantry Regiment and later the division, becoming the only civilian recruiting agency in military history.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army planners favored recruiting experienced skiers for the unit instead of trying to train standing troops in mountain warfare, so Dole recruited from schools, universities, and ski clubs for the unit.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 87th trained in harsh conditions, including Mount Rainier's 14,411-foot (4,392 m) peak, throughout 1942 as more recruits were brought in to form the division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Initial training was conducted by Olympian Rolf Monsen.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] A new garrison was built for the division in central Colorado at Camp Hale, at an elevation of 9,200 feet (2,800 m) above sea level.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The **10th Light Division (Alpine)** was constituted on 10 July 1943 and activated five days later at Camp Hale under the command of Brigadier General Lloyd E.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Culin Jr. assigned as his assistant division commander (ADC).
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Light Division was centered on regimental commands; the 85th, 86th, and 87th Infantry Regiments.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division faced many difficulties in the new training, which had no established army doctrine.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Light Division was unique in that it was the only division in the army with three field artillery battalions instead of four.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] It was equipped with vehicles specialized in snow operation, such as the M29 Weasel, and winter weather gear, such as white camouflage and skis specifically designed for the division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division practiced its rock climbing skills in preparation for the invasion of Italy on the challenging peaks of Seneca Rocks in West Virginia.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Its specialized training culminated with what were known as the "D-Series" ("D" for "Divisional"), military maneuvers on the divisional level in the Colorado Rockies in Winter conditions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Beginning 26 March 1944, the exercises were intended to last five weeks.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The soldiers endured an adverse environment, and "tactical conditions" that banned open fires in sub-zero temperatures.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] As a result, the exercises were ended after 3 weeks.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Official statistics recorded 195 cases of frostbite and 340 other incapacitating injuries.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 22 June 1944, the division was shipped to Camp Swift, Texas, to prepare for maneuvers in Louisiana, which were later canceled.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] A period of acclimation to a low altitude and hot climate was thought necessary to prepare for this training.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 6 November 1944, the 10th Division was redesignated the **10th Mountain Division**.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] That same month, the blue and white "Mountain" tab was authorized for the division's new shoulder sleeve insignia.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Also in November, the division received a new commander, Brigadier General George Price Hays, a Medal of Honor recipient and a distinguished veteran of World War I.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On January 4, 1945, he received a promotion to major general.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division sailed for the Italian front in two parts, with the 86th Infantry and support leaving Camp Patrick Henry, Virginia on 11 December 1944 aboard the SS *Argentina* and arriving in Naples, Italy on 22 December.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 85th and 87th Infantry left Hampton Roads, Virginia on 4 January 1945 aboard the SS *West Point* and arrived on 13 January 1945.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 6 January, its support units were preparing to head to the front lines.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] It was attached to Major General Willis D.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Crittenberger's IV Corps, part of the American Fifth Army, commanded by Lieutenant General Lucian Truscott.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 8 January, the 86th Infantry had moved to Bagni di Lucca near Mount Belvedere in preparation for an offensive by the Fifth Army to capture the mountain along with surrounding high ground, which allowed the Axis to block advances to Po Valley.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Starting 14 January, the division began moving to Pisa as part of the Fifth Army massing for this attack.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 20 January, all three of the 10th's regiments were on or near the front line between the Serchio Valley and Mt.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Barlow commanded the 85th Regiment, Col.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] While the Brazilian division was in charge of taking Monte Castello and *Castelnuovo* di Vergato, the 10th Mountain Division was responsible for the Mount Belvedere area, climbing nearby Riva Ridge during the night of 18 February and attacking Mount della Torraccia on 20 February.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] These peaks were cleared after four days of heavy fighting, as Axis troops launched several counterattacks in these positions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In early March, the division fought its way north of Canolle and moved to within 15 miles (24 km) of Bologna.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 5 March, while Brazilian units captured Castelnuovo, the 85th and the 87th Infantry took respectively Mount Della Spe and Castel D'Aiano, cutting the Axis routes of resupply and communication into the Po Valley, setting the stage for the next Fifth Army offensive.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division maintained defensive positions in this area for three weeks, anticipating a counteroffensive by the German s.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In the final days of April 1945, as German defenses in northern Italy collapsed, the 10th Mountain Division advanced north toward Lake Garda in pursuit of retreating s.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The difficult terrain and destroyed infrastructure around the lake required the use of amphibious DUKW vehicles for transport and assault.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On the night of 30 April, one such vehicle carrying 25 soldiers sank during the crossing, resulting in one of the last and most tragic losses of the Italian campaign.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] That same day, the division's newly appointed Assistant Commander, Colonel William Orlando Darby—founder of the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army Rangers—was killed by artillery fire in Torbole, together with Sergeant Major John T.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The events at Lake Garda marked the final combat actions for the 10th Mountain Division in Europe and have since become a lasting symbol of the cost of liberation.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Their story, long preserved by veterans and local historians, was later chronicled through research and documentary projects led by Italian and American collaborators, including Associazione Benàch and the 2023 film *The Lost Mountaineers*.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division resumed its attack on 14 April 1945, pressing forward on multiple axes.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] That day it assaulted Torre Iussi and Rocca Roffeno, north of Mount Della Spe.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] After stiff fighting, on 17 April it broke through the German Gothic Line defenses, opening the way into the Po Valley.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Over the next days the advance continued: on 20 April the 10th captured Mongiorgio and pushed into the Po plain, taking key positions at Pradalbino and Bomporto.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division crossed the Po River at San Benedetto Po on 23 April, reached Verona on 25 April, and encountered heavy resistance in the areas of Torbole and Nago.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Because the routes around Lake Garda had been rendered impassable by destroyed tunnels and bridges, the division carried out an amphibious crossing of the lake using DUKW vehicles.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 30 April it secured Gargnano and Porto di Tremosine on the western shore, effectively ending organized German resistance in northern Italy.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] That same night, however, a tragic accident occurred.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] During a night operation to transport troops and equipment across Lake Garda from Torbole toward the northern shore, one DUKW carrying 25 men of the 10th Mountain Division sank in deep water during rough weather.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The vehicle, heavily loaded with men, a 75 mm pack howitzer, ammunition, and gear, began taking on water and foundered before rescue could reach it.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Hough, survived; the others were declared Missing in Action (MIA) and remain unaccounted for.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The site of the sinking remained unknown for decades, despite repeated efforts by the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army, local divers, and underwater archaeology teams.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2012, after several unsuccessful surveys, the Italian volunteer rescue group Volontari del Garda located the wreck upright on the lakebed using sonar and remotely operated vehicles.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The ongoing research and commemorative work were later supported by the Italian historical association Associazione Benàch, which collaborated with local authorities and U.S. veterans’ families to preserve the memory of the missing soldiers.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 2023 documentary *The Lost Mountaineers*, produced by the Fondazione Museo Storico del Trentino in collaboration with Associazione Benàch, chronicles these final days of combat and the search for the lost soldiers.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The film reconstructs the events leading to the sinking, the experiences of the men aboard, and the decades-long recovery efforts.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] It also situates the tragedy within the wider story of the 10th Mountain Divisions campaign in northern Italy and its human cost.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On the same day, 30 April 1945, the division also suffered the loss of its Assistant Division Commander, Colonel William O.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] While in Torbole on the northern shore of Lake Garda, Darby was killed by an enemy artillery shell explosion along with his Sergeant Major, John T.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Darby had been appointed to the division only days earlier, following the wounding of Brigadier General Robinson E.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Duff, and was directing the final movements of the divisions advance when he was struck by shrapnel.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] His death came just hours before the announcement of the German surrender in Italy.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] After the German capitulation on 2 May 1945, the division shifted to security and occupation duties.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 5 May it reached Nauders, Austria, just beyond the Reschen Pass, where it linked up with elements of the U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Between 2 May and Victory in Europe Day (8 May), the 10th Mountain Division accepted the surrender of German units and secured key areas in northeastern Italy and western Slovenia.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 20 May it had redeployed to Udine, joining the British Eighth Army to prevent further westward movement of Yugoslav troops.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In July, the Department of War assigned the 10th Mountain to the Pacific theater; after a month's furlough the men would assemble at Camp Carson, where they would train for Operation Downfall, the invasion of mainland Japan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Between 26 July and 2 August the three regiments boarded ships for the return voyage to the United States; the day before the first of these regiments, the 86th Mountain Infantry, disembarked at Hampton Roads, Hiroshima was leveled by an atom bomb.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Three days after the rest of the division landed stateside on 11 August, Japan officially surrendered.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division was demobilized and inactivated on 30 November 1945 at Camp Carson, Colorado.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] During World War II, the 10th Mountain Division suffered 992 killed in action and 4,154 wounded in action in 114 days of combat.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Soldiers of the division were awarded one Medal of Honor (John D.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Magrath), three Distinguished Service Crosses, one Distinguished Service Medal, 449 Silver Star Medals, seven Legion of Merit Medals, 15 Soldier's Medals, and 7,729 Bronze Star Medals.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division itself was awarded two campaign streamers.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In June 1948, the division was rebuilt and activated at Fort Riley, Kansas to serve as a training division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Without its "Mountain" tab, the division served as the 10th Infantry Division for the next ten .
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The unit was charged with processing and training replacements in large numbers.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] This mission was expanded with the outbreak of the Korean War in 1950.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 1953, the division had trained 123,000 new Army recruits at Fort Riley.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 1954, the division was converted to a combat division once again, though it did not regain its "Mountain" status.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Using equipment from the deactivating 37th Infantry Division, the **10th Infantry Division** was deployed to Germany in 1955, replacing the 1st Infantry Division at Würzburg, serving as part of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) defensive .
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division served in Germany for four , until it was rotated out and replaced by the 3rd Infantry Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division moved to Fort Benning, Georgia, and was inactivated on 14 June 1958.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 13 February 1985, the 10th Mountain Division (Light Infantry) was reactivated at Fort Drum, New York.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In accordance with the Reorganization Objective Army Divisions plan, the division was no longer centered on regiments, instead two brigades were activated under the division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 1st Brigade, 10th Mountain Division (commanded by then Colonel John M.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Keane, later 4-Star General and Army Vice Chief of Staff) and Division Artillery were activated at Fort Drum, while the 2nd Brigade, 10th Mountain Division was activated at Fort Benning, moving to Fort Drum in 1988.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division was also assigned a round-out brigade from the Army National Guard, the 27th Infantry Brigade.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division was specially designed as a light infantry division able to rapidly deploy.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In this process, it lost its mountain warfare capability, but its light infantry organization still made it versatile for difficult terrain.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Equipment design was oriented toward reduced size and weight for reasons of both strategic and tactical mobility.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division also received a distinctive unit insignia.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 1990, the division sent 1,200 soldiers to support Operation Desert Storm.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Two infantry platoons from the division were among those sent: 1st Platoon Bravo Company 1/22 and the 1/22 Scout Platoon.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Once in Iraq, the scouts were sent home and First Platoon was left as a counterintelligence .
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Performing three-man 24hr patrols through the remainder of their deployment, this platoon was widely regarded as the division's best at that time.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Following a cease-fire in March 1991, the support soldiers began redeploying to Fort Drum through June of that year.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Hurricane Andrew struck South Florida on 24 August 1992, killing 13 people, leaving another 250,000 homeless, and causing damages in excess of $20 billion.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 27 August 1992, the 10th Mountain Division assumed responsibility for Hurricane Andrew disaster relief as Task Mountain.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Division soldiers set up relief camps, distributed food, clothing, medical necessities, and building supplies, as well as helping to homes and clear debris.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The last of the 6,000 division soldiers deployed to Florida returned home in October 1992.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 3 December 1992, the division headquarters was designated as the headquarters for all Army s (ARFOR) of the Unified Task (UNITAF) for Operation Restore Hope.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Arnold, the division Commander, was named Army s commander.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division's mission was to secure major cities and roads to provide safe passage of relief supplies to the Somali population suffering from the effects of the Somali Civil War.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Due to 10th Mountain Division efforts, humanitarian agencies declared an end to the food emergency and factional fighting decreased.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] When Task Ranger and the SAR team were pinned down during a raid in what later became known as the Battle of Mogadishu, the 10th Mountain Division provided infantry for the UN quick reaction sent to rescue them.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division had two soldiers killed in the fighting, which was the longest sustained firefight by regular U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division began a gradual reduction of s in Somalia in February 1994, until the last soldiers of the 2nd Battalion, 22nd Infantry returned to the United States in March 1994.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division formed the nucleus of the Multinational Haiti (MNF Haiti) and Joint Task 190 (JTF 190) in Haiti during Operation Uphold Democracy.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] More than 8,600 of the division's troops deployed during this operation.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 19 September 1994, the 1st Brigade conducted the Army's first air assault from aircraft carrier USS *Dwight D.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] This consisted of 54 helicopters and almost 2,000 soldiers.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] They occupied the Port-au-Prince International Airport.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] This was the largest Army air operation conducted from a carrier since the Doolittle Raid in World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division's mission was to create a secure and stable environment so the government of Haitian President Jean-Bertrand Aristide could be reestablished and democratic s held.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] After this was accomplished, the 10th Mountain Division handed over control of the MNF-Haiti to the 25th Infantry Division on 15 January 1995.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division redeployed the last of its soldiers who served in Haiti by 31 January 1995.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In the fall of 1998, the division received notice that it would be serving as senior headquarters of Task Eagle, providing a peacekeeping to support the ongoing operation within the Multi-National Division-North area of responsibility in Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Selected division units began deploying in late summer, approximately 3,000 division soldiers deployed.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] After performing their mission in Bosnia, the division units conducted a transfer of authority, relinquishing their assignments to soldiers of the 49th Armored Division, Texas National Guard.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] By early summer 2000, all 10th Mountain Division soldiers had returned safely to Fort Drum.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] During the 2000 presidential , the readiness of the 10th Mountain Division became a political issue when George W.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Bush asserted that the division was "not ready for duty." He attributed the division's low readiness to the frequent deployments throughout the 1990s without time in between for division elements to retrain and refit.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] General Accounting Office in July 2000 also noted that although the entire 10th Mountain Division was not deployed to the contingencies at once, "deployment of key components—especially headquarters—makes these divisions unavailable for deployment elsewhere in case of a major war".
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Conservative think tank The Heritage Foundation agreed with these sentiments, charging that the U.S. military overall was not prepared for war due to post–Cold War drawdowns of the U.S. military.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Army responded that, though the 10th Mountain Division had been unprepared following its deployment as Task Eagle, that the unit was fully prepared for combat by late 2000 despite being undermanned.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Still, the Army moved the 10th Mountain Division down on the deployment list, allowing it time to retrain and refit.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2002, columnist and highly decorated military veteran David Hackworth again criticized the 10th Mountain Division for being unprepared due to lack of training, low physical fitness, unprepared leadership, and low morale.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] He said the division was no longer capable of mountain warfare.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] These concerns were quickly debunked as the 10th Mountain Division was the first conventional unit in the entire US military to be deployed to Afghanistan, seeing heavy combat.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Following the 11 September 2001 attacks, elements of the division, including its special troops battalion and 1st Battalion, 87th Infantry Regiment (1-87th) infantry deployed to Afghanistan as part of Operation Enduring Freedom in late 2001.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] This was the first conventional unit to be deployed in the entire US military.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division headquarters arrived at Karshi-Khanabad Air Base, under Major General Franklin L.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Hagenbeck, on 12 December 2001 to function as the Combined s Land Component Command (CFLCC) (Forward).
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] This command served as the representative for Lieutenant General Paul T.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army/CFLCC commanding general (CG) in the theater of operations.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division was also intended to defend Uzbekistan against attacks by the Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan, which was seeking to overthrow Islam Karimov's secular government.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 13 February 2002, Mikolashek ordered Hagenbeck to move CFLCC (Forward) to Bagram airfield located at Bagram and 2 days later the headquarters was officially redesignated as Combined Joint Task (CJTF) Mountain.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] It assumed responsibility for the planning and execution of what had then become known as Operation Anaconda.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Elements of the division, primarily 1-87th Infantry, remained in the country until mid-2002, fighting to secure remote areas of the country and participating in prominent operations such as Operation Anaconda, the Fall of Mazar-i-Sharif, and the Battle of Qala-i-Jangi.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] These 1-87th Infantry soldiers became the first U.S. conventional s to fight in Afghanistan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division also participated in fighting in the Shahi Khot Valley in 2002.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In June 2002, elements of the 82nd Airborne Division arrived to relieve CJTF Mountain, and in September, Major General John R.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Vines and his Combined Task 82 relieved CJTF Mountain as the major subordinate headquarters to Combined Joint Task 180.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Upon the return of the battalions, they were welcomed home and praised by President Bush.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2003, the division's headquarters, along with the 1st Brigade, returned to Afghanistan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] During that time, they operated in the frontier regions of the country such as Paktika Province, going to places previously untouched by the war in search of Taliban and Al-Qaeda s.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Fighting in several small-scale conflicts such as Operation Avalanche, Operation Mountain Resolve, and Operation Mountain Viper, the division maintained a strategy of small units moving through remote regions of the country to interact directly with the population and drive out insurgents.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 1st Brigade also undertook a number of humanitarian missions.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2003 and into 2004, the division's aviation brigade deployed for the first time to Afghanistan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] As the only aviation brigade in the theater, the brigade provided air support for all U.S.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade's mission at that time focused on close air support, medevac missions, and other duties involving combat with Taliban and Al-Qaeda s in the country.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division was the first unit to introduce contract working dogs into southern Afghanistan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In the spring of 2004, they had Patriot K-9 Services supply 20 dog teams based at KAF.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The teams were trained to detect explosives and perform patrol duties throughout the region.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade returned to Fort Drum in 2004.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On the return of the division headquarters and 1st Brigade, the 10th Mountain Division began the process of transformation into a modular division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 16 September 2004, the division headquarters finished its transformation, adding the 10th Mountain Division Special Troops Battalion.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 1st Brigade became the 1st Brigade Combat Team, while the 3rd Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division was activated for the first time.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In January 2005, the 4th Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division was activated at Fort Polk, Louisiana.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] 2nd Brigade Combat Team would not be transformed until September 2005, pending a deployment to Iraq.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In late 2004, the 2nd Brigade Combat Team was deployed to Iraq supporting Operation Iraqi Freedom.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 2nd Brigade Combat Team undertook combat operations in western Baghdad, an area of responsibility that included Abu Ghraib, Mansour, and Route Irish.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Around that time, the 1st Brigade Combat Team deployed back to Iraq, staying in the country until 2006.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The next time the 1st Brigade Combat Team was deployed was during the Surge for 15 months in Iraq.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Northern Iraq was the theater of operations for 1 BCT from August 2007 until November 2008.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 4th BCT operated in Northeast Baghdad under the 4th Infantry Division headquarters from November 2007 until January 2009.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain participated in larger-scale operations, such as Operation Phantom Phoenix.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] After a one-year rest, the headquarters of the 10th Mountain Division was deployed to Iraq for the first time in April 2008.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division headquarters transferred authority for MND-S to the 34th Infantry Division, Minnesota Army National Guard on 20 May 2009.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 2nd Brigade Combat Team was scheduled to deploy to Iraq in the fall of 2009, as a part of the 2009–2010 rotation to Iraq.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division headquarters, the 3rd Brigade Combat Team, and two Battalion Task s from the 4th Brigade Combat Team deployed to Afghanistan in 2005, staying in the country until 2006.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division and brigade served in the eastern region of the country, along the border with Pakistan, fulfilling a similar role as it did during its previous deployment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] During this time, the deployment of the brigade was extended along with that of the 4th Brigade, 82nd Airborne Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] It was eventually replaced by the 173rd Airborne Brigade Combat Team which was rerouted from Iraq.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In the winter of 2006, the 10th Aviation Brigade, 10th Mountain Division, was deployed again to Afghanistan to support Operation Enduring Freedom as the only aviation brigade in the theater, stationed at Bagram Air Base, Afghanistan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Named "Task Falcon," the brigade's mission was to conduct aviation operations to destroy insurgents and anti-coalition militia in an effort to help build the Afghan National Security 's capability and allow the Afghan government to increase its capabilities.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In addition, the Task provided logistical and combat support for International Security Assistance s throughout the country.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 3rd Brigade Combat Team was slated to deploy to Iraq in 2009, but that deployment was rerouted.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In January 2009, the 3rd BCT instead deployed to Kunar, Logar and Wardak Provinces, eastern Afghanistan to relieve the 101st Airborne Division, as part of a new buildup of US s in that country.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade was responsible for expanding forward operating bases and combat outposts (COPs) in the region, as well as strengthening US military presence in preparation for additional US s to arrive.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 1st Brigade Combat Team was scheduled to deploy to Iraq in late 2009 but deployed instead to Afghanistan in March 2010 for 13 months.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] 1-87th Infantry deployed to Kunduz and Baghlan Provinces, establishing remote combat outposts (COPs) against the Taliban after they had taken control of these provinces over the last several .
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Brigade again deployed to Afghanistan in late 2012 to Ghazni Provence for nine months.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 3rd Brigade Combat Team deployed to Kandahar Province, southern Afghanistan in March 2011, again relieving the 101st Airborne Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] During this deployment, 3rd BCT mainly occupied forward operating bases (FOBs) and combat outposts (COPs) in the Maywand, Zhari, and Arghandab Districts of Kandahar Province.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade was redeployed to Fort Drum in March 2012 after a twelve-month deployment.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 4th Brigade Combat Team deployed to Regional Command East, under the 101st Airborne Division from October 2010 until their redeployment in October 2011.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 4th BCT deployed to both Wardak and Logar provinces.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] During this deployment, they went to places such as Chakh Valley in Wardak Province and Charkh Valley in Logar Province in search of elements of the Haqqani Network.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In May 2013, the brigade deployed again to Afghanistan returning home in February 2014.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 5 December 2019, the Department of the Army announced that the 1st Brigade Combat Team would replace the 3rd Brigade Combat Team, 82nd Airborne Division as part of a unit rotation in support of Operation Freedom's Sentinel.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade deployed to Afghanistan in February 2020.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 3 November 2016, *Stars and Stripes* reported that the 10th Combat Aviation Brigade would deploy 1,750 soldiers to Eastern Europe in March 2017, in support of Operation Atlantic Resolve – as part of NATO efforts to reassure Eastern Europe in response to Russian intervention in Ukraine in 2014.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade arrived with approximately 60 aircraft, including CH-47 Chinooks, UH-60 Blackhawks, and medevac helicopters.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade was headquartered in Germany and the brigade's units were forward-based at locations in Latvia, Romania, and Poland.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Between late summer and early fall 2015, as well as again in 2016, 1,250 soldiers from the 1st Brigade Combat Team were deployed to Iraq to support Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] During the two deployments the brigade spent in Iraq, they fought to regain control of the cities of Ramadi, Fallujah, and Mosul from the Islamic State of Iraq and Syria.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2022 the unit would redeploy again, in support of Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division was awarded two campaign streamers in World War II, one campaign streamer for Somalia, and four campaign streamers in the war on terrorism, for a total of seven campaign streamers and three unit decorations in its operational history.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Note that some of the division's brigades received more or fewer decorations depending on their individual deployments.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2026, the Army announced that it has officially approved the formerly unauthorized ski trooper insignia to be worn on the AGSU garrison cap for soldiers in the 10th Mountain Division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Skiing associations subsequently contend that veterans of the 10th Mountain Division had a substantial effect on the post–World War II development of skiing as a vacation industry and major sport.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Ex-soldiers from the 10th laid out ski hills, designed ski lifts, became ski coaches, racers, instructors, patrollers, shop owners, and filmmakers.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] They wrote and published ski magazines, opened ski schools, improved ski equipment, and developed ski resorts.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Up to 2,000 of the division's troops were involved in skiing-related professions after the war, and at least 60 ski resorts were founded by men of the division.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] People associated with the 10th Mountain Division later went on to achieve notability in other fields.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Bill Bowerman, former executive director and Sierra Club leader David R.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Brower, former United States Ski Team member World War II civilian mountaineer trainer H.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Additionally, five members of the division have been awarded the Medal of Honor.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Magrath became the first member of the division to receive this award (posthumously) during World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Monti, received it posthumously in 2009, for actions during a combat operation on 21 June 2006 in Afghanistan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Swenson, received it in 2013, for actions on 8 September 2009, during the Battle of Ganjgal in Afghanistan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] Atkins, received it posthumously on 27 March 2019, for actions on 1 June 2007 during a patrol in Iraq.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The fifth, Michael Ollis, received it posthumously on 2 March 2026, for actions on 28 August 2013 during an attack in Afghanistan.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division's efforts in Afghanistan during Operation Enduring Freedom and beyond led to the division being referred to as the "Tribe of Crossed Swords" by some Afghans.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division's first appearance in popular literature was the semi-fictional novel by Frank Harper, *Night Climb*, published in 1946 by Longsman, Green, and Company.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The title of this book came from the unit's celebrated night ascent of Riva Ridge as part of the Battle of Mount Belvedere, and the novel follows the actions of several members through Operation Encore and Operation Craftsman to the end of hostilities in Italy.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Division was later the subject of the 1996 film *Fire on the Mountain*, which documented its exploits during World War II.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division is also a prominent element of the book *Black Hawk Down* and film *by the same name*, which portrays the Battle of Mogadishu and the division's participation in that conflict.
[src:10th-mountain-division/10th-mountain-division-p01] John, referencing his time spent with the 10th Mountain Division in Afghanistan.
